<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gordon Struggling in CART </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Robby Gordon, the only owner-driver in the CART  
FedEx Series, is having a frustrating time at the Toronto Molson 
Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, who nearly won the Indianapolis 500 in May, running out  
of fuel while leading with just two laps remaining, qualified 22nd 
among the 27 drivers on hand for Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	As one of the slower qualifiers on Friday in the opening round  
of time trials, Gordon was placed with the slower of two groups in 
Saturday's split qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have no idea how hard it is to go out there and drive the  
wheels off something and still wind up 22nd,'' Gordon said. ``I'm 
watching the fast group go through the last turn here and I can see 
how these guys are hooked up. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, I've got my hands completely full right there. It's  
hard to find a solution right now. But we're working like dogs out 
here to make it right. Unfortunately, we're scratching like dogs, 
too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All is not gloom for Gordon, though. Despite his recent  
qualifying woes, Gordon has finished among the top 10 in each of 
the last two races. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's proved the last few weeks that he can come through the  
field and post a good finish regardless of where he starts,'' noted 
team manager and co-owner Mike Held. ``So we're optimistic about 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GETTING BETTER:@ Gil de Ferran's pole victory on Saturday gave  
Goodyear it's second pole in 11 events this season. The first was 
last month in Cleveland, also by de Ferran. 
</P>
<P>
	De Ferran's victory in the race at Portland, Ore., last month  
also ended a losing streak by Goodyear that began after Michael 
Andretti won the 1998 season-opener in Homestead, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of this season, Andretti and Newman-Haas Racing  
teammate Christian Fittipaldi both switched to Firestones, leaving 
de Ferran's Walker Racing, Marlboro Team Penske, Dan Gurney's All 
America Racers and Bettenhausen Racing as the only Goodyear teams. 
</P>
<P>
	De Ferran, who is now Goodyear's main CART test driver, said,  
``We continue to pick it up every race. There's been a big 
improvement in the tires since last year. They are really 
consistent and just getting better every race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perry Bell, Goodyear's CART operations manager, said, ``With a  
pole position and second-place finish on an oval (in Japan), a win 
and second-place on road courses (Portland and Cleveland), and now 
a pole on a street course, Goodyear has proven the competitiveness 
of its CART tires on each of the different race circuits we race 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Memo Gidley, de Ferran's rookie teammate, was the next fastest  
Goodyear qualifier Saturday. He will start 15th. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH:@ Earlier this season, when 28-year-old  
Christian Fittipaldi outqualified 36-year-old teammate Michael 
Andretti, he quipped, ``Maybe you're just getting too old for this 
stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four times this season, Fittipaldi has outqualified 1991 CART  
champion Andretti. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Saturday, Andretti outqualified his Newman-Haas Racing  
teammate for the third straight race and Fittipaldi said, ``You 
must be getting younger, my friend, because you are qualifying 
quicker than me now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPARK PLUGS: Al Unser Jr. will make his 265th career start  
Sunday, breaking a tie with retired Bobby Rahal for the all-time 
CART lead in that category. Adrian Fernandez makes his 100th start, 
joining Unser, Michael Andretti (240), Scott Pruett (135), Paul 
Tracy (122) and Jimmy Vasser (117) as the only active drivers with 
at least 100. ... Drivers with Honda engines have won the last nine 
CART races contested on temporary street circuits, dating to the 
beginning of 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
