<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> George Magazine, JFK Jr.'s Vision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After years of indecision, John F. Kennedy made  
up his mind in 1995: his immediate future was in publishing, not 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-prosecutor, at a jam-packed Manhattan news conference,  
announced plans for George -- a magazine that he envisioned as a 
Rolling Stone of politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not just politics as usual,'' was the magazine's tagline.  
</P>
<P>
	Four years later, the glossy magazine was in danger of  
disappearing, as ad pages and circulation fell. In the six months 
ending Dec. 31, 1998, paid circulation was down 5 percent to 
403,894. And ad pages this year were down 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's four-year deal with parent company Hachette Filipacchi  
expired at the end of this year, raising questions about the 
magazine's future. The company and one of Kennedy's partners spent 
$20 million to launch the magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine debuted four years ago with a splash: supermodel  
Cindy Crawford donned a white wig and little else to pose as George 
Washington. The celebrity covers became the magazine's trademark. A 
cover photo of Drew Barrymore evoked Marilyn Monroe's birthday 
serenade to President Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine was non-partisan; recent additions to its staff  
included ex-U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a Republican, and Clinton 
White House adviser Paul Begala. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize a Kennedy talking about non-partisan is like Mark  
Furhman addressing an NAACP convention,'' he joked at the news 
conference annoucing the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy, while the magazine's publisher, was also a contributor.  
He conducted interviews with the Rev. Billy Graham, ex-Alabama Gov. 
George Wallace and Mike Tyson. 
</P>
<P>
	He also ruffled family feathers by describing -- in a September  
1997 magazine column -- cousins Michael and Joseph Kennedy as 
``poster boys for bad behavior'' after each had very public marital 
woes. 
</P>
<P>
	George contributing editor Douglas Brinkley described Kennedy as  
a ``terrific editor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``John had a great sense of humor and sense of self-deprecation,  
and a trickster side to him,'' Brinkley said Saturday from his 
Louisiana home. 
</P>
<P>
	At the magazine's Manhattan offices, nobody was speaking  
Saturday as the search continued. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this time, we are not offering any statement,'' said a man  
answering the phone. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
