<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newark Team Returns With Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Baseball returned to Newark on Friday night  
with a wild pitch from Yogi Berra, a sea of purple jerseys and the 
cheers of a struggling city that has a home team for the first time 
in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newark Bears, the nation's top minor-league team in the  
1930s and 1940s, returned to the city as a franchise of the 
independent Atlantic League to play on the edge of the Passaic 
River in the 6,014-seat Riverfront Stadium -- at $34 million, one of 
the most expensive minor-league ballparks in America. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials hope the stadium will revive baseball's glory  
days in the state's largest city, when the Newark Bears and the 
Negro League's Newark Eagles were champions. The teams quit the 
city after 1949 and the old stadium was torn down two decades 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be like it was way back in the good old days,''  
said Hall of Famer Phil Rizzuto, one of several New Jersey baseball 
greats who attended the Bears' opening game. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also hope the stadium, like a performing arts center  
built downtown two years ago, will help revitalize a city that has 
never completely recovered from race riots in the 1960s, and still 
has trouble keeping people downtown at night. 
</P>
<P>
	Burt Ironson, Elliott Sudler and Mace Chaplowitz remember a  
different Newark. The 70-year-old Newark natives can still recite 
the Newark Bears lineup from the 1940s, when they were high school 
classmates and attended every game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Newark was a beautiful, vibrant city in those days,'' said  
Ironson, a retired judge from Springfield. ``It's facilities like 
this that will bring people back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berra, who played for the Bears in the 1940s before becoming a  
Hall of Famer for the New York Yankees, started the action with a 
ceremonial pitch that sailed over the glove of team owner Rick 
Cerone, a former Yankees catcher. Cerone caught Berra's second try. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's great,'' said Berra, signing autographs for fans  
and some of the Bears in the dugout. ``I think it's going to keep 
the kids off the streets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Screaming fans eating hot dogs, drinking beer and lining up to  
buy purple Newark Bears jerseys and hats didn't seem to notice when 
the home team went down 3-0 to the Lehigh Valley Black Diamonds in 
the first inning. They cheered wildly at every strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears went on to win the game, 9-8, in 10 innings.  
</P>
<P>
	``I always wanted to go to a baseball game,'' said 11-year-old  
Eric Nunez, who isn't counting the games he plays for the Little 
Ironbound League in a Portuguese neighborhood of Newark. ``I'm very 
happy because it's my first time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other kids practiced their curveballs at a speed pitch tent or  
sought autographs from practicing players. Ryan Long, who plays 
right field for the Bears, spent the hour before the game signing 
balls and programs. The team, which has a 25-37 record this year, 
has played a season and a half outside of Newark, hosting ``home'' 
games at Skylands Park in Augusta. The team is scheduled to play 36 
games this year at Riverfront Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just excited to have a place we can call home,'' Long  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
