<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Lifts U.S. Jews' Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the view of many American Jews, Benjamin  
Netanyahu left office as an icon of the right wing who blocked 
Israeli peacemaking. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, his successor as prime minister, Ehud Barak, is shadowed by  
the opposite reputation -- a man open to compromise who will bring a 
quick peace with the Arabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither caricature is true,'' says Elan Steinberg, executive  
director of the New York-based World Jewish Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The new Israeli leader, his country's most decorated soldier,  
was elected in May as Americans were wringing their hands over 
renewed violence between Israelis and Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Now on his first visit to the United States, Barak -- whose name  
means ``lightning'' in Hebrew -- has become a lightning-rod for 
American Jewish expectations across the political spectrum. 
</P>
<P>
	In The Washington Post on Friday, an ad from Americans for Peace  
Now wished Barak ``continued strength'' in seeking peace. In the 
New York Post, opponents of the peace process expressed fear in 
another ad that Barak might make too many concessions to 
Palestinians under American pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. Jewish leaders say the average American Jew is willing  
to give Barak a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is, Barak comes here with an abundance of good  
will,'' said Steinberg. ``There is no questioning his courage, his 
determination to secure peace while protecting Israeli security. 
The danger is, the expectations are so high -- the expected rapid 
advances of the peace process over a short time period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That attitude was reflected on Manhattan's Upper West Side, a  
traditional bastion of liberal Jewish views. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's committed to a rapid peace, he's conciliatory,''  
said Jane Edelson, an editor shopping at the Zabar's deli. ``I'm 
not a Zionist, I believe Palestinians have rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, on a subway train rolling toward midtown, law professor  
Lloyd Epstein cradled a mammoth book of Hebrew doctrine as he 
offered his support for the new Israeli leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak ``is not really a new figure -- only in the American  
media,'' said Epstein. ``He's not unlike many Israeli leaders -- 
(the late Prime Minister Yitzhak) Rabin, for instance, who was a 
military man and worked for peace. It's not a contradiction. And 
everyone's hopes are the same as before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Standing at the other end of the car was Stephen Garrin,  
professor of Judaic studies at Baruch College and a Netanyahu 
supporter. He agreed with Epstein that the two Israeli politicians 
are not as far apart politically as their American images. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's face it, they're both hard-liners. Barak is a military  
man who knows what the score is with the Arabs,'' said Garrin. 
``He's just more sophisticated, he has more finesse in dealing with 
people, he doesn't fly off the handle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Barak wields his new power, U.S. supporters of Netanyahu are  
under pressure to take a more middle-of-the-road approach to any 
peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a political minefield.  
</P>
<P>
	The One Israel Fund/Yesha Heartland Campaign, a group that funds  
Jewish West Bank settlements, pointedly warned Barak in a statement 
to tell President Clinton ``that Israel will not be pressured into 
any negotiations, and Israeli sovereignty over Jerusalem is not 
subject to discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More cautious was Ronald Lauder, heir to the cosmetics fortune  
who is both a friend of Netanyahu and head of the Conference of 
Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The interesting thing is, both men have their priorities  
exactly the same -- Israel's security and peace in the region,'' 
said Lauder, who was to meet Barak on Sunday. ``American Jews will 
support the prime minister of Israel 100 percent, no matter who he 
is, because we have one Israel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever their stances, American Jews' high expectations of the  
neophyte prime minister ``will have to be tempered,'' warns 
Steinberg of the World Jewish Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we say in Brooklyn,'' he added, tongue-in-cheek, ``it ain't  
going to be easy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
