<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rights Leader Farmer Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- James L. Farmer, the last of the ``Big  
Four'' civil rights leaders, was remembered as the ``tallest of the 
giants'' in the fight to end segregation -- the man who refused to 
accept ``whites only'' signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jim was not just for the black race. He was for the human  
race,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, along with other civil rights leaders and politicians,  
paid tribute to Farmer on Friday at a service at Virginia Union 
University, a stop on the Freedom Rides he initiated in the 1960s 
to help desegregate interstate busing. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmer, of Fredericksburg, died July 9. The public memorial  
service attracted several hundred people. His funeral was private. 
</P>
<P>
	``We honor his memory by staying in the struggle,'' said Dorothy  
Height, past president of the National Council of Negro Women and 
longtime friend of Farmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Added former Virginia Gov. L. Douglas Wilder: ``It is our  
responsibility to make certain our young people never forget that 
James Farmer had to spend the better part of his life fighting for 
things most Americans take for granted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Farmer's father asked him during college what he planned to  
do with his life, he had a two-word reply: ``Destroy segregation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At age 22, Farmer founded the Congress of Racial Equality. He  
became one of the most visible national civil rights leaders, along 
with Martin Luther King Jr., NAACP chief Roy Wilkins and Urban 
League leader Whitney Young. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the tallest of the giants,'' said Jackson.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1942, a dozen years before the Montgomery bus boycott, Farmer  
led a sit-in at a Chicago restaurant that barred blacks. He missed 
one of the defining events of the civil rights movement -- the 1963 
March on Washington -- because he was in jail in Alabama for trying 
to enter a whites-only bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, President Clinton presented him with the Presidential  
Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Atlanta Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMPTON, Ga. (AP) -- A.J. Foyt got a major scare Saturday before  
the Indy Racing League cars even got on the track at Atlanta Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Foyt's 22-year-old son, Larry, was involved in a spectacular  
five-car crash during a Formula 2000 race prior to the IRL's Kobalt 
Mechanics Tools 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Foyt's car flipped in the air and burst into flames,  
but he managed to stagger away from the mangled wreckage after it 
came to a stop. He collapsed on the grass inside the track, while 
his father lumbered from the pits to render assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Foyt suffered bruises and a minor burn on his left  
arm. He was treated at the infield hospital and released. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was banged up pretty good,'' said A.J. Foyt, who owns the  
cars of IRL pole-sitter Billy Boat and defending series champion 
Kenny Brack. ``He'll be hurting tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The most seriously injured drivers were Larry Oberto and Arnold  
Brinkman, who suffered concussions and were taken by helicopter to 
Atlanta Medical Center. Like Foyt, Tom Wood and Michael Curtis were 
released after treatment at the infield center. 
</P>
<P>
	The wreck occurred on lap 19 of the 34-lap race when the tightly  
bunched field approached the start-finish line in front of the 
grandstands. Jonathan Bottoms swerved into Brinkman, setting off 
the chain-reaction crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Brinkman took out Foyt, whose car flipped, struck the wall and  
was slammed by Wood, engulfing both open-wheelers in flames. The 
race was red-flagged and then halted due to time constraints, 
giving the victory to pole-sitter Steve Rikert. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope the drivers are OK,'' Rikert said in a somber  
Victory Lane. ``We're competitors, but we're more like family and 
friends. Certainly, you don't like to see something like that 
happen in the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RAY'S LUCK:* Greg Ray wasn't sure why his car quit running, but  
he knows how to prevent it from happening again. Pack your bags, 
wife and kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, who won the previous IRL race at Pikes Peak and finished  
second before that at Texas, was leading the Kobalt Mechanics Tools 
500 when a mechanical problem knocked him out on lap 108. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were running strong,'' Ray said. ``I don't know what  
happened. A chain broke or something like that. One thing I do 
know: My wife and kids have been to the last two races and I 
finished first and second. My wife and kids will definitely be at 
Dover (for the next race) because they are good luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray and his wife, Angela, have two children, 6-year-old Winston  
and 1-year-old Simon. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NEW FENCE:* A higher fence, installed in front of the  
grandstands after three fans were killed at Charlotte on May 1, got 
its first test during the Formula 2000 crash. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three pieces of debris deflected off the new fence,  
which stands 21 feet high and extends 6 feet over the track. The 
old fence was 15 feet high and extended out 3 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, track officials closed off the first 15 rows in the  
main grandstand. 
</P>
<P>
	The fans didn't seem too concerned for their own safety,  
standing to watch as the F2000 crash occurred in right in front of 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mainly, I was concerned for the safety of the drivers,'' said  
Buddy Hitt of Live Oak, Fla. ``I wasn't really worried about the 
fans. Charlotte and Michigan (where an Indy-car crash killed three 
fans in 1998), that was something of a freak.'' 
</P>
<P>
	None of the crashes during the IRL race occurred in front of the  
grandstands, which were sparsely filled anyway. The crowd was 
estimated at just 30,000. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOUBLE DUTY:* Three-time Indianapolis 500 winner Johnny  
Rutherford was grand marshal of the race in addition to his normal 
duties as pace-car driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Rutherford gave the command to start the race using a wireless  
microphone from the pace car. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gentleman, start your engines and follow me,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Rutherford won the inaugural Indy-car event at Atlanta in 1965  
and swept two 125-mile races at the track in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT FILLERS:* Track officials used the IRL race to announce a  
new title sponsor for the NASCAR Busch series race held at the 
track in March. Aaron's Rental Purchase will lend its name to the 
event under a three-year deal that runs through 2002. ... The 
Lazier brothers, Buddy and Jacques, didn't have to look hard to 
find each other. Buddy started the race from the 15th spot on the 
inside of the eighth row -- with his younger brother right beside 
him in the 16th position. Both took turns with the lead before 
crashes took them out. Jacques finished 12th, Buddy 21st. ... The 
race began at 7:30 p.m., causing treacherous conditions as the sun 
was setting behind turn one. Several drivers complained that it was 
hard to see until the sun disappeared beyond the horizon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
