<HEADLINE> Smoltz Pain-Free in Rehab Stint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- John Smoltz pitched two more pain-free  
innings for Atlanta's Double-A Greenville affiliate Saturday night, 
then pronounced himself ready to rejoin the Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 Cy Young Award winner gave up five hits and two runs in  
the first two innings of Greenville's 6-3 win over Jacksonville. He 
struck out three and walked one. 
</P>
<P>
	More importantly, Smoltz said there was no pain in the right  
elbow that has bothered him off and on for more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really pleased with the fact that at the present moment my  
elbow feels pretty good,'' Smoltz said. ``I didn't quite have the 
location of the pitches that I would like. All in all, I'm really 
happy. I came in here expecting the worst and I came out with some 
hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander also pitched two innings Thursday as he worked  
his way back from inflammation that landed him on the disabled list 
July 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz expects to rejoin the Braves in Miami for their series  
against the Florida Marlins on Wednesday. He will throw once on the 
side before an expected start next Saturday at Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``My biggest problem is patience and waiting,'' Smoltz said.  
``Now I have to wait a few more days to judge this elbow and see 
how it does. If I feel fine, I'm going to make my start, which 
looks like Saturday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz is 8-3 with a 3.49 ERA in 15 starts.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
