<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Irked Over Bush Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- State Republican Party leaders say they  
were paid with out-of-state ``soft'' money for the lease on a prime 
site that Texas Gov. George W. Bush will use next month to court 
activists at a big straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides and party leaders insist the move is legal, an  
argument rejected by a rival. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides to publisher Steve Forbes say the expenditure violates  
campaign finance laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``This raises serious questions about how ethical a Bush  
administration would be, particularly since they've raised a 
gazillion dollars from Washington lobbyists,'' said spokesman Keith 
Appel. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Mindy Tucker, spokeswoman for the Republican presidential  
front-runner, said it's legal and that ``we play by the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa Republican Party Executive Director Dee Stewart confirmed  
the state party was paid with out-of-state checks that didn't come 
from the Bush campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``From our perspective, a straw poll is a fund-raiser for the  
party, it's not an election,'' said Stewart. ``It's perfectly 
acceptable for a presidential candidate to encourage people to 
donate money to the Republican Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart said the party was paid with six separate checks, and a  
receipt given to the person delivering the checks. He said he was 
unsure whether that person was affiliated with a campaign, but 
insisted the party acted within the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are well within state and federal guidelines,'' said  
Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the campaigns have leased space outside of Hilton  
Coliseum in Ames next month to throw parties for supporters showing 
up for the straw poll, considered an early test of candidate 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush paid the most, spending $43,000 to rent the spot. By  
contrast, Elizabeth Dole spent $5,500 for her site. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker conceded the money, actually paid to the Iowa Republican  
Party, came from soft money from out of state. She said the move 
was legal and the spending allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Soft money is cash donated directly to political parties instead  
of candidates and is largely unregulated by federal campaign 
finance laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an efficient use of our resources,'' Tucker said.  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes aide Bill Dal Col disagreed, saying the expenditure  
violated campaign finance laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be three or four separate violations,'' Dal Col said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
