<HEADLINE> Time Heirs Won't Preserve Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHESTER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- The sons of Time magazine founder  
Henry R. Luce have put the family estate up for sale after 
rejecting a plan to sell half of it to the government as farmland 
preserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Luce III and Peter Paul Luce were in negotiations to sell  
the development rights to 80 acres of the 166-acre property to the 
Morris County agricultural development board for $1.86 million, 
county officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The board sets aside money to buy up open space and save it from  
development. 
</P>
<P>
	But the brothers lost interest after learning that the county  
and township couldn't come up with all the money for the land right 
away, Peter Paul Luce said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the person who wants to buy a car for let's say  
$10,000, but they've only got $5,000,'' said Luce, 70, of 
Englewood, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	They are now asking $9.5 million on the open market for the  
estate, with its 21-room mansion and miles of views of the Somerset 
Hills. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Luce and Lila Hotz Luce Tyng built the estate, called Lu  
Shan, in 1933, about a decade after Luce founded the Time Inc. 
magazine empire. Mrs. Tyng received the home two years later after 
the couple divorced. She died in March. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
