<HEADLINE> New Weather Terms Abound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- It's not the heat, it's the humidity. Or is it the  
dew point? What about the heat index? 
</P>
<P>
	As high temperatures abound this summer, you may be hearing  
fewer references to humidity -- the traditional measure of muggy, 
sticky weather -- and more talk of dew points and heat indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	Meteorologists have used these ``new'' buzz words internally for  
years but are taking them public to replace or supplement weather 
terms frequently lost on the public. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you say the humidity is 50 percent, I don't think that  
really means a lot to people,'' said meteorologist Michael Henry. 
</P>
<P>
	Meteorologists point to ``relative humidity'' as a frequently  
misunderstood weather term. 
</P>
<P>
	It refers to how much moisture the air can hold at a certain  
temperature. Because it is expressed as a percentage, that alone 
makes it a poor indicator for the public of what the weather feels 
like outside, meteorologists said. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, dew point readings are expressed as single numbers  
-- like temperatures -- and give a better indication of outdoor 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	For most people, at dew point readings of 50 or below, the air  
outside feels comfortable. When readings creep into the 60s, many 
start to feel uncomfortable as excessive moisture in the air 
prevents sweat from evaporating. At levels above 70, nearly 
everyone feels oppressed by wet, muggy air. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier to work with than percentages,'' said Dennis  
Smith, a meteorologist with The Weather Channel in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	By definition, the dew point is the temperature the air must be  
cooled down to for moisture to come out of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Another good indicator of how hot it is outside is the heat  
index -- similar to wind chill readings in the winter. The heat 
index is a combination reading of the temperature and dew point and 
indicates how hot it feels outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just say its like wind-chill in reverse,'' said Ed Carroll,  
a meteorologist with Boston's WBZ-TV. ``It feels hotter than it 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters say that 'round the clock weather information on the  
Internet and cable television has helped the general public 
understand the terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``People know that if the heat index is above 100 the weather is  
going to be pretty bad outside,'' said Joe Dellicarpini, a 
meteorologist with the National Weather Service. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
