<HEADLINE> Crane Supervisor Concerns Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A union leader says iron workers, upset over a  
crane collapse that killed three men, won't resume work on the 
Milwaukee Brewers new baseball stadium until a supervisor of crane 
lifts is removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he isn't replaced, we're not going back to work,'' said  
Brent Emons, business manager for Iron Workers Local 8, which 
represents many Miller Park workers, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The supervisor was not identified.  
</P>
<P>
	A giant crane lifting a roof section of Miller Park, the new  
$400 million home of the Brewers, collapsed in winds gusting up to 
26 mph Wednesday, killing three workers and injuring five others. 
</P>
<P>
	Emons and some iron workers have said workers felt it had been  
too windy to make the lift of the 400-ton section of the ballpark's 
retractable roof. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just feel that it was a bad call, and we won't be put in  
that position again,'' Emons said. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers have been off since the accident. They are due to  
report back to work on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Cannon, a spokeswoman for Mitsubishi, the stadium's roof  
contractor, said Friday that the job status of the lift supervisor 
mentioned by Emons had not changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's in the same position and has the same responsibilities,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyle Balistreri, president of the Milwaukee Building and  
Construction Trades Council, said unions have an agreement 
prohibiting work stoppages at the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an extremely serious issue,'' he said. ``We do not  
sanction what is happening here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal safety inspectors doing an unannounced safety inspection  
at the site when the crane collapsed apparently had no concerns 
about the safety of the operation, said Jim Dollins, of the 
Occupational Safety and Health Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have said they don't yet know what the accident will  
do to the timetable for completing Miller Park, which had been due 
to open next April. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
