<HEADLINE> 100 Homeless After Spokane Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- More than 100 people were left homeless  
and one firefighter injured due to a fire that destroyed most of a 
downtown city block. 
</P>
<P>
	The early Friday blaze, which started in a vacant three-story  
brick building, rapidly spread to a six-story apartment building 
with 90 units. Many of the residents, mostly elderly and low-income 
people, fled in little more than bathrobes. 
</P>
<P>
	The buildings that were destroyed date from the turn of the  
century and are some of the city's oldest. Authorities say 108 
people are now without homes. 
</P>
<P>
	A column of black smoke hung over downtown well into the  
afternoon. Charred embers littered streets for several blocks. 
</P>
<P>
	A firefighter was knocked unconscious after a ceiling collapsed,  
but she was treated and released from a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms was called  
in to help pinpoint the cause of the blaze. 
  	   	
</P>
