<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JFK Jr.'s Plane Reported Missing  
</P>
<P>
	MATTITUCK, N.Y. (AP) -- An intensive search is under way today  
for John F. Kennedy Jr., whose small plane is missing en route to a 
family wedding in Massachusetts. The only son of the 35th president 
was traveling with his wife Carolyn Bessette, and her sister, the 
Coast Guard said. The Piper Saratoga took off from Essex Airport in 
Caldwell, N.J., at 8:45 p.m. yesterday and was heading to the Cape 
Cod-Martha's Vineyard area en route to a wedding today in 
Hyannisport, Mass. The passengers were due to arrive in Martha's 
Vineyard at 10 p.m. yesterday, but never arrived, a source told The 
AP. Coast Guard crews scoured a 150-mile-long swath of sea today 
from eastern Long Island to Cape Cod. 

</P>
<P>
	Kennedy Compound Wedding Postponed  
</P>
<P>
	HYANNISPORT, Mass. (AP) -- At the storied compound here that has  
been a refuge of the Kennedy family for decades, the setting was 
prepared for a wedding today, but it had to be postponed. Family 
members and friends gathered for the wedding of Rory Kennedy had 
learned that the plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr. and his wife to 
the wedding was missing. A Mass began on the porch of the house of 
Rory's mother, Ethel Kennedy, with about 50 family members and 
three priests praying ``for the safety of the loved ones,'' a 
family spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Decries GOP Tax Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax cuts of the size proposed by Republicans  
in Congress would ``blow a $3 trillion hole'' in the federal budget 
just as baby boomers retirement strains Medicare and Social 
Security, President Clinton said today. In his weekly radio 
address, Clinton cited a new Treasury Department analysis showing 
the House GOP plan to cut taxes by $864 billion over 10 years would 
cost more than three times that in the decade after 2009. In the 
Republican response, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson said deep tax 
cuts he helped enact in his state beginning in 1986 have now 
translated into $5,600 less in taxes for the average Wisconsin 
family. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Fines Anti-Abortion Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered national  
anti-abortion leaders to pay more than $257,000 in damages and to 
stop interfering with the operation of abortion clinics across the 
country. U.S. District Judge David Coar yesterday barred the 
leaders from blocking clinic doors and driveways, damaging clinic 
property and threatening violence against doctors and patients 
anywhere in the nation for the next 12 years. Those named as 
defendants were Joseph Scheidler, head of the Chicago-based 
Pro-Life Action League, the league itself, Operation Rescue and two 
other activists. 

</P>
<P>
	TWA Relatives Marking 3rd Anniversary  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Relatives of those killed in the crash of TWA  
Flight 800 will hold a memorial today, the third anniversary of the 
crash. The service will be held near where the plane plunged into 
the Atlantic Ocean shortly after take-off from New York, killing 
230 people. Though a criminal probe has been closed, the actual 
crash investigation remains open. The reconstructed plane still 
sits in a hangar in Long Island. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Says Montenegro Split Possible  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia and Montenegro, the two  
republics that make up Yugoslavia, may split for good if they fail 
to agree on redefining their mutual relations, a top Serb official 
said today. Bogoljub Karic, a Serbian government minister without 
portfolio, said it was better for Montenegro to have full 
independence than autonomy with just 5 percent representation in 
the Yugoslav federation, according to Vijesti newspaper. Talks 
began earlier this week between delegations from the two republics. 

</P>
<P>
	Saddam Says Israelis Should Leave  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- President Saddam Hussein said today that  
Iraq will not give up its fight against Israel until the Jews leave 
the region or live as citizens under a Palestinian Arab state. In a 
speech marking the 31st anniversary of the coup that brought his 
party to power, Saddam said other Arab leaders feel the same way 
but were reluctant to tell the Israelis. ``Palestine is Arab. The 
Zionists must depart from it,'' Saddam said. His remarks came as 
Israel's new Prime Minister Ehud Barak is vowing to speed up the 
Mideast peace process. 

</P>
<P>
	Parry Makes Charge at British Open  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Australia's Craig Parry, who began  
the day eight shots off the lead at the British Open, birdied six 
holes today to move within three shots of Frenchman Jean Van de 
Velde. Parry was 5-under for the day through 16 holes and 4-over 
for the tournament. Van de Velde faltered early, making a bogey on 
the second hole, but came back with a birdie to get back to 1-over 
and lead by two shots over Sweden's Patrik Sjoland. Greg Norman 
birdied the first hole to get to 3-over, but then bogeyed the next 
two. Tiger Woods is 4-over, two shots back. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
