<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serbia, Montenegro Split Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia and Montenegro, the two  
republics that make up Yugoslavia, may split for good if they fail 
to agree on redefining their mutual relations, a top Serb official 
said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bogoljub Karic, a Serbian government minister without portfolio,  
said it was better for Montenegro to have full independence than 
autonomy with just 5 percent representation in the Yugoslav 
federation, according to Vijesti newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Karic also said that if the two republics failed to agree on how  
to live together, ``there remains nothing else but for us to 
separate in a democratic and civilized manner,'' according to the 
Belgrade-based private news agency, Beta. 
</P>
<P>
	While Karic said Montenegro could maintain ``quality relations''  
with dominant Serbia, where ``each is the master in his own 
house,'' he emphasized that the joint state must be based on 
existing constitutional rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strongest Montenegrin party must be in the federal  
government, and have the post of premier as well,'' Karic told 
Vijesti. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks began earlier this week in Belgrade between delegations  
from the two republics. Montenegro's pro-Western government hopes 
the talks might lead to Yugoslavia becoming a looser federation. 
But Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is unlikely to agree to 
relenting power. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of a split puts pressure on Serb officials to  
consider ousting Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serb-born American millionaire, Milan Panic, who served as  
federal premier and backs Serbia's anti-Milosevic movement, told 
Belgrade daily Blic that, if Milosevic remains in power, 
``everything has been prepared for Montenegro to secede.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 08:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Not Riding on Dad's Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush is emerging from his  
father's shadow in his presidential fund raising, gleaning a 
smaller percentage of contributions in the last quarter from people 
who previously gave to his father's White House campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just shows that he's not riding on his father's coattails  
by any means,'' said Bruce Buchanan, political scientist at the 
University of Texas at Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	An Associated Press computer analysis found that 11.8 percent of  
the Texas governor's itemized individual contributions in the 
latest reporting period came from people who had given to his 
father in 1988 or 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the elder Bush gave $3.23 million out of the  
Republican front-runner's $27.5 million in the April-June quarter, 
according to records the governor filed with the Federal Election 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	In the previous reporting period, 15.4 percent of Bush's  
itemized contributions came from his father's supporters -- or $1.06 
million of $6.9 million. The AP analysis looked at individual 
contributions of more than $200. 
</P>
<P>
	Political experts see the shrinking percentage as a good sign  
for the younger Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	It's crucial for him to broaden his support beyond that held by  
his father if he hopes to emulate his successful presidential 
effort and not his losses, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``You need only remember that his father got 38 percent of the  
vote in 1992 to realize that if he can't greatly broaden his 
father's coalition, he will simply not win,'' said Larry Sabato, 
director of the Center for Governmental Studies at the University 
of Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabato said he had expected a higher percentage of Bush's  
contributions to come from his father's backers but said the 
smaller percentage is very good for Bush's candidacy. He suggested 
it would be good strategy for Bush to try to separate himself from 
his father. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's in this race, in part, because of his name, so he owes a  
lot to his father. Before this is over, if he is the nominee, he is 
going to pay for that connection,'' Sabato said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Democrats will focus extensively on the shape of the  
economy at the end of the Bush administration versus the shape of 
the economy under the Clinton administration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Goldford, chairman of the Department of Politics and  
International Relations at Drake University in Des Moines, Iowa, 
agreed that the smaller percentage of dad-related money is a 
positive sign for Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``It suggests he's expanding his base beyond people who merely  
might have supported his father and therefore would support him,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Bush didn't demonstrate overwhelming popularity even  
when he won in 1988 with only 53 percent of the popular vote in an 
election against Michael Dukakis and that Democrat's ``abysmally 
terrible campaign,'' Goldford said. 
</P>
<P>
	``His name isn't George Reagan, it's George Bush,'' Goldford  
said. ``If his name were George Schleppermeyer, he probably 
wouldn't have had that initial stake from people. That certainly 
helped. But he's not a puppet or clone of his father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, he said, the younger Bush appears to be a much  
better campaigner. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Miller, director of the Iowa Social Science Institute at  
the University of Iowa in Iowa City, had a different appreciation 
of the 11.8 percent tally. He called it a percentage significant 
enough to suggest family loyalty. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is drawing upon the same constituency that his father drew  
upon, despite the fact that one of the messages he is trying to 
convey to the broader public is that he is reaching out beyond the 
normal sorts of people that the Republicans would normally draw 
into their support groups,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Hughes, the candidate's spokeswoman, said it's  
unsurprising that people who supported the father would support the 
son. They're likely to be Republicans, many are friends, and a 
number may have worked with him during his father's campaigns, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what the number also says is, look at the 90 percent  
who contributed to Governor Bush who did not contribute to his 
father,'' she said. ``What that will say is Governor Bush is 
succeeding in attracting support from people who may have never 
been involved politically before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Bush, who is unrelated, organized more than 300  
fund-raisers for the former president. He said the crowd at a 
recent Washington fund-raiser for the younger Bush is a good sign 
of broad support. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old Bush group was there, and they were there in force.  
But there was a whole new group of people that I had never heard of 
before. I think that bodes well,'' Fred Bush said. ``I think it 
says there's huge pent-up demand for leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bush took in $1 million at a June 22 fund-raiser attended  
by many lobbyists and by members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	By the numbers, the AP analysis found that of 34,620 reportable  
contributions totaling $27.5 million in the last reporting period, 
there were 3,677 totaling $3.23 million from people who also gave 
to Bush's father in 1988 or 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Of 8,669 reportable contributions totaling $6.9 million in the  
first reporting period, 1,350 totaling $1.06 million came from 
people who also gave to Bush's father in 1988 or 1992. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 08:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
