<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yes It's True Wins DeFrancis Dash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUREL, Md. (AP) -- Yes It's True solidified his standing as the  
country's top sprinter, driving late to beat Good And Tough by 
three-quarters of a length in the $300,000 Frank J. DeFrancis 
Memorial Dash on Saturday at Laurel. 
</P>
<P>
	The D. Wayne Lukas-trained colt, carrying seven more pounds then  
any other entrant, won his fourth straight start, finishing six 
furlongs in 1:08.67. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-5 betting favorite, with Jerry Bailey aboard, paid $3.40,  
$2.20 and $2.10. Good And Tough was worth $2.40 and $2.10, and 
Storm Punch, a locally trained longshot, returned $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes It's True started three wide and was third for most of the  
race. He made his big push in the stretch, overtaking Storm Punch 
and holding off Good and Tough. 
</P>
<P>
	The lone 3-year-old in a six-horse field, Yes It's True won for  
the sixth time in eight starts this year after earlier victories in 
Gulfstream's Swale Stakes, Keeneland's Lafayette Stakes, Pimlico's 
Maryland Breeders' Cup Handicap, Belmont's Riva Ridge Stakes and 
Monmouth's Jersey Shore Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Good and Tough, who had won four of his past five starts, broke  
slowly and played catch-up much of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The DeFrancis, elevated to Grade I status for the first time  
this year, is the only top-level six-furlong race in North America 
outside of the Breeders' Cup Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	The race, named after a former Laurel CEO, has produced three  
sprint champions in the past nine years, as well as four Eclipse 
Award winners. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
