<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy Search Forces TV Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The search for John F. Kennedy Jr.'s missing  
plane forced the networks to alter their sports programming, with 
ABC switching its British Open golf coverage Saturday to fellow 
Disney-owned ESPN and the Major League Soccer All-Star game to 
ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS wasn't as fortunate. It had to scrap its broadcast of the  
Ameritech Seniors Open golf tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC was scheduled to show the third round of the British Open  
starting at 10 a.m. EDT, but instead stayed with the breaking story 
involving the search for Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN picked up coverage about 11:30 a.m. EDT and stayed with the  
British Open, instead of regularly scheduled fishing and rodeo 
programming, until the leaders finished. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a breaking news story of national importance that took  
priority over any program we had scheduled on ABC,'' said an ABC 
spokesman. ``Fortunately, we had ESPN so we were able to switch the 
viewers who wanted to watch the Open championship while staying 
with the unfolding news story on ABC news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The MLS All-Star game in San Diego was supposed to start on ABC  
at 3:30 p.m., but was switched to ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS' broadcast of the Ameritech Seniors Open was scheduled to  
air from 4-6 p.m. EDT. CBS offered local affiliates a 15-minute 
highlight package, according to tournament director Brian 
Fitzgerald. The network's international coverage continued 
uninterrupted. 
</P>
<P>
	``This pretty much is a decision made in New York,'' Fitzgerald  
said. ``It's an unfortunate situation. We don't have much power 
over what's going on. All three networks made the decision to go 
with coverage of the search.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fitzgerald acknowledged that not having TV coverage could hurt  
tournament attendance for Sunday. The Saturday broadcast creates 
awareness and excitement, especially if it's a close tournament and 
there's a big name on the leaderboard. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time the tournament has been pre-empted,  
Fitzgerald said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never for the entire day,'' he said. ``We've been pre-empted  
before because other sports coverage has run late. But nothing to 
this extent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox pre-empted its pregame baseball show, ``In the Zone'', but  
went ahead with its baseball game of the week that included 
occasional news updates. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC was supposed to show the LPGA Big Apple Classic golf  
tournament at 2 p.m. and a WNBA game between Los Angeles and 
Phoenix at 4 p.m., but it switched them to its CNBC cable channel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
