<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Records Open to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After months of controversy, some 5,700 boxes of  
records from the 1996 Summer Olympics will be made available to the 
public beginning Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents, which range from sponsorship contracts to  
documents related to the design and development of venue sites, 
created conflict between Olympic organizers and congressional 
investigators looking into possible corruption in the bid for the 
1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need this kind of information for a whole lot of  
purposes,'' said Penn State University professor John Lucas, a 
historian who has written four books on the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Journalists and historians are far apart in a number of  
things, but they are both investigators seeking the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Payne, former chief of the now-defunct Atlanta Committee  
for the Olympic Games, decided to released the bulk of the records 
in an effort to quell the controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	ACOG will hold on to eight boxes that officials maintain include  
private information -- such as lists of donors wishing to remain 
anonymous, letters subject to attorney-client privilege and 
personnel files. 
</P>
<P>
	However, congressional investigators, who opened their  
investigation following bribery allegations involving the 2002 
Games in Salt Lake City, will have access to all records, including 
the eight sensitive boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	An attempt to open those eight boxes to the public is in the  
works. A ruling on a lawsuit filed over whether the Georgia Open 
Records Act applies to the records kept by the Georgia Amateur 
Athletics Foundation, which coordinated Atlanta's bid for the 1996 
Olympics, is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	ACOG, meanwhile, has compiled an inventory of the contents of  
all the boxes, which are being housed at the Atlanta History Center 
and in private storage facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Monday, the three-year anniversary of the Atlanta  
opening ceremonies, the records will be available for public 
viewing. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents may include unseen material such as sponsorship  
contracts and television rights negotiations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
