<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kennedy Visual Aerial Search Suspended  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- The daylong search Saturday for the  
missing plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and 
sister-in-law yielded only some fragments of Kennedy's 
red-and-white plane, a piece of baggage labeled with the business 
card of Lauren Bessette, sister of Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and a 
prescription bottle belonging to Bessette Kennedy. State police 
said late Saturday that the visual aerial search had been suspended 
until Sunday at daybreak, but an Air National Guard helicopter with 
infrared sensors would continue searching overnight in the dark. 

</P>
<P>
	Kennedys Top News Around World  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British newspapers featured stories Sunday on the  
search for the missing Kennedy plane, while broadcasters throughout 
Europe led newscasts with the disappearance of John F. Kennedy Jr., 
his wife and her sister. Some British newspapers referred to the 
Kennedy family's history of tragedy, a theme echoed across Europe. 
Kennedy's disappearance topped French TV news Saturday with reports 
on the search, profiles of Kennedy's life and special reports 
devoted to the Kennedys. Kennedy was traveling with his wife, 
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette, to a 
family wedding when their plane disappeared. 

</P>
<P>
	War Prosecutor Urges Rehabilitation  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Local courts in the former  
Yugoslavia must be rehabilitated so that they eventually can help 
handle some of the growing caseload, the chief prosecutor for the 
international war crimes tribunal said today. Louise Arbour is on 
her last tour of the region before leaving her post in The Hague, 
Netherlands. ``I think that it's critical that we participate and 
assist in full rehabilitation of domestic courts so that they can 
undertake a significant share of prosecuting war criminals,'' she 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	E. Timor Annexation Date Observed  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Anti-independence fighters and government  
officials commemorated the anniversary of Indonesia's 1976 forced 
annexation of East Timor on Saturday, just weeks before a 
U.N.-organized vote on the territory's future. The provincial 
governor appealed for calm ahead of the August ballot, which will 
determine whether mainly Roman Catholic East Timor will become an 
autonomous region within Muslim-dominated Indonesia or break away 
altogether. 

</P>
<P>
	India Declares End of Kashmir Fight  
</P>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- India's defense minister declared the end  
of fighting in Kashmir Saturday following the withdrawal of Muslim 
guerrillas from Himalayan battle zones under an agreement with 
Pakistan. Indian troops reclaimed key mountains and advanced to the 
1972 cease-fire line with Pakistan in all but one of four battle 
zones. The soldiers planned to reoccupy the fourth zone soon. India 
had given Pakistan a Friday deadline -- later extended to early 
today -- for the insurgents to retreat from key peaks they captured 
in May on India's side of the cease-fire line. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombian Guerrilla Threat Decried  
</P>
<P>
	LA TUNIA, Colombia (AP) -- A top rebel leader says Colombia's  
military is exaggerating the threat posed by leftist guerrillas and 
inflating their battlefield prowess to gain U.S. counterinsurgency 
aid. The charges came as Colombia's defense minister visited 
Washington to lobby for increased assistance a week after a bloody 
guerrilla offensive in which the military claimed it had rescued 
the capital, Bogota, from a rebel takeover attempt. 

</P>
<P>
	Farrakhan Says Health Is Improving  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan said  
Saturday night that he is nearly rid of cancer and recovering from 
an ulcer caused by radiation treatments. Speaking by telephone 
intercom to an audience gathered at a restaurant to celebrate the 
20th anniversary of the Nation of Islam's newspaper, the Final 
Call, Farrakhan sounded upbeat during his 15-minute address. ``I 
believe within the next few months that ulcer will be completely 
healed and that your brother will be back with you,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Yankees Beat Braves 11-4  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Andy Pettitte, squarely on the trading block  
during a disappointing season, survived one bad inning Saturday and 
helped the Yankees beat the Atlanta Braves 11-4. Bernie Williams 
and Chuck Knoblauch homered early, and the Yankees batted around in 
a five-run fifth to block the Braves' bid for a three-game sweep. 
Atlanta had won four in a row overall. 

</P>
<P>
	Phillies Beat Red Sox 11-3  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Randy Wolf became the first Philadelphia pitcher  
in 19 years to win his first five decisions, and Ron Gant drove in 
five runs, including a two-run homer, as the Phillies extended 
Boston's interleague woes with an 11-3 victory Saturday. Mark 
Lieberthal and Doug Glanville each had four hits for the Phillies, 
who posted 18 hits. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
