<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Ronald Yurcak    	
</P>
<P>
	FAR HILLS, N.J. (AP) -- Ronald N. Yurcak, a junk bond trader who  
worked closely with Michael Milken, died Tuesday of a heart attack. 
He was 57. 
</P>
<P>
	Ross Perot, the founder of Electronic Data Systems Corp., hired  
Yurcak in 1971 as a systems engineer. Yurcak also worked as Perot's 
personal assistant and in the brokerage subsidiary of EDS, a 
computer services company in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Yurcak later moved to Kidder Peabody &AMP; Co. and to Merrill Lynch.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, he moved to Salomon Brothers, where he started and  
managed the high-yield bond trading and sales department. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, Yurcak moved to Drexel Burnham Lambert in Beverly  
Hills, Calif., where Milken had moved the firm's junk bond 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Yurcak was one of eight traders there, buying and selling  
billions in junk bonds, which are debt securities issued by 
corporations with poor credit ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	After the collapse of Drexel Burnham Lambert, he went to work  
for a succession of financial companies in the United States and 
Hong Kong. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Touts Education in Iowa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- President Clinton, on a one-day visit to  
the state that launches the presidential primary season, offered 
hope of quick federal relief to farmers suffering tough economic 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know we've got a terrible problem in farm country all over  
America,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While three GOP presidential hopefuls crisscrossed the state for  
votes, Clinton reminded his listeners that he wasn't a candidate in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	But he sounded like one, challenging Republicans in Congress to  
take advantage of the healthy economy to invest in education and 
Social Security before promising tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of them think politics is about power and position, but  
we think it's about ideas and people,'' Clinton said Friday at a 
fund-raiser for Sen. Tom Harkin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Save Social Security and Medicare first, pay down the debt and  
take care of education,'' he said. ``Then give the country a tax 
cut. That's what we believe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GOP favorite Gov. George W. Bush criticized Clinton's  
agriculture policies on Thursday, saying his administration has 
done little to ease the pressures on the nation's farmers. Without 
referring to Bush directly, Clinton tried to lay blame for the 
farmers' problems on policies generated by the 
Republican-controlled Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	He said those who supported the Freedom to Farm Act, which  
weaned farmers away from price supports in exchange for more 
freedom to choose what they planted, ``acted like there never would 
be a bad day on the farm.'' Clinton signed the legislation into law 
but said that he would soon seek changes in it. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also met for an hour with seven Iowa farmers to discuss  
the economic difficulties they're facing at a time of historically 
low commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a listening session,'' said White House spokesman Barry  
Toiv. ``They took the opportunity to impress upon the president how 
serious the problems are facing Iowa farmers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowans pleaded with Clinton for emergency assistance.  
</P>
<P>
	The president didn't commit himself, but Toiv said ``he was very  
sympathetic'' and promised to have his staff and Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman examine the request immediately. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
