<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2:40 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Plane Debris Found on Mass. Beach  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- An intensive search is under way today  
along the Atlantic seaboard for a small plane carrying John F. 
Kennedy Jr. to a family wedding in Massachusetts, the Coast Guard 
said. The only son of the nation's 35th president was traveling 
with his wife and his sister-in-law. Hours after the search began, 
Coast Guard Lt. Craig Jaramillo confirmed the discovery on Philbin 
Beach on Martha's Vineyard, of ``some luggage,'' a wheel, headrest 
and part of a plane support known as a strut. He would not confirm 
reports that the luggage contained items with the name of Lauren 
Bessette, Kennedy's sister-in-law, who was reportedly aboard the 
aircraft. 

</P>
<P>
	Search for Kennedy Plane Narrows  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Coast Guard and Air Force narrowed their  
search for a missing plane carrying John F. Kennedy Jr. and two 
others to an area off the coast of their intended destination, 
Martha's Vineyard, Mass., after debris was spotted today. ``We are 
centering our search about 17 miles west of Martha's Vineyard,'' 
said Coast Guard Rear Adm. Richard Larrabee. Officials said at 
least 20 aircraft and two boats are participating in the search. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Decries GOP Tax Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax cuts of the size proposed by Republicans  
in Congress would ``blow a $3 trillion hole'' in the federal budget 
just as baby boomers retirement strains Medicare and Social 
Security, President Clinton said today. In his weekly radio 
address, Clinton cited a new Treasury Department analysis showing 
the House GOP plan to cut taxes by $864 billion over 10 years would 
cost more than three times that in the decade after 2009. In the 
Republican response, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson said deep tax 
cuts he helped enact in his state beginning in 1986 have now 
translated into $5,600 less in taxes for the average Wisconsin 
family. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Kosovo Chief Visits Torn City  
</P>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Bernard Kouchner, the new  
U.N. administrator of Kosovo, arrived today in this divided city 
where ethnic Albanians and Serbs form two hostile camps on opposite 
sides of the Ibar river. Prior to Kouchner's arrival, ethnic 
Albanians called off an anti-Serb protest in an apparent attempt to 
avoid possible violence in this northern city. Also today, about 
200 reservists took to the streets of Serbia's largest southern 
city, Nis, demanding long overdue payment for their services and 
ignoring a plea for patience from a top Yugoslav army general. 

</P>
<P>
	Kashmir Withdrawal Completed  
</P>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- Islamic fighters completed their withdrawal  
to beyond the India-Pakistan cease-fire line today, a senior Indian 
army commander said, effectively ending a two-month battle in the 
icy heights of Kashmir. Brig. Ramesh Kakar said Indian soldiers 
reaching the cease-fire line in the Mushkoh Valley could see small 
remaining groups of fighters trekking over mountain passes into 
Pakistan. The Mushkoh Valley was the last battle zone where some 
rival forces had lingered. Some 1,100 fighters on both sides were 
killed in the conflict, and hundreds more wounded. 

</P>
<P>
	Grocer Settles Discrimination Suit  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Winn-Dixie has agreed to pay $33  
million to settle racial and sexual discrimination claims brought 
by employees of the supermarket chain. The settlement was announced 
by the company yesterday, the same day the class-action lawsuit was 
filed in federal court by 13 current and former employees. The 
settlement, which covers all Winn-Dixie stores, could apply to more 
than 50,000 black or female employees who have worked for the chain 
since 1993. The settlement must be approved by U.S. District Court. 

</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde Opens 4-Stroke Lead  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- France's Jean Van de Velde used a  
huge birdie putt on the 14th hole today to get back to even par in 
the third round of the British Open, and is four ahead of his 
nearest challengers after 16 holes at 1-over. Craig Parry shot the 
lowest round to move into a tie for second at 5-over with Justin 
Leonard. Tiger Woods and Greg Norman, meanwhile, both struggled. 
Woods shot a 74 and was six back at 7-over while Norman bogeyed the 
last hole for a 75 and was 8-over. 

</P>
<P>
	49ers Give Receiver Owens 7-Yr Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Wide receiver Terrell Owens has reached a  
7-year contract agreement with the San Francisco 49ers worth at 
least $23 million, the San Francisco Chronicle reported today. The 
contract includes a signing bonus of $7.5 million and an escalator 
clause that could push the total value of the deal to as much as 
$35 million, the newspaper said. Last season, Owens had 67 
receptions for 1,097 yards and 14 touchdowns, including a 79-yard 
scoring catch. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
