<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts on Search for JFK Jr.'s Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The search for John Kennedy Jr.'s small plane ranged over some  
1,000 square miles at its height. A look at the aircraft and 
vessels involved: 
</P>
<P>
	--Two Coast Guard HH-60 Jayhawk helicopters searching from  
Martha's Vineyard to tip of Long Island. The twin-engine 
medium-range aircraft can fly 300 miles offshore, then hover for 45 
minutes, pick up six people and return with a safe fuel reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	--Coast Guard HU-25 Falcon jet searching Long Island. Falcon can  
operate from sea level to 42,000 feet and has an operating range of 
2,045 nautical miles. 
</P>
<P>
	--Two HC-130 turboprop Hercules cargo planes, one serving as  
airborne command circling the search area and the other searching 
waters off south shore of Long Island. They are from the New York 
Air National Guard and include the same crew that searched the 
crash site of TWA Flight 800 three years ago Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	--15 single-engine light aircraft from Civil Air Patrol units in  
New York, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut and New Jersey, 
searching over land and along shorelines. Supported by 156 
volunteers, the planes are owned privately or by the Air Force. 
</P>
<P>
	--Variety of Coast Guard boats and police and civilian vessels.  
</P>
<P>
	--HH-60G Pave Hawk helicopter from New York Air National Guard.  
Equipped with all-weather radar, in-flight refueling capability and 
a rescue hoist able to lift 600 pounds, and looks similar to the 
Jayhawk. 
</P>
<P>
	--National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration research vessel  
on standby for possible undersea search. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
