<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed Tax Cuts in Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A comparison of the highlights for individuals of tax relief  
packages proposed in the House and Senate. 

</P>
<P>
 *INCOME TAXES   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Across the board 10 percent cut in income tax  
rates, phased in over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: Cut bottom income tax bracket from 15  
percent to 14 percent beginning in 2001. Gradually expand income 
levels eligible for 14 percent bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: Increase standard deduction by $4,350 for  
joint filers, $1,300 for single filers. 

</P>
<P>
 *MARRIAGE PENALTY   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Allow married couples to claim a standard  
deduction of $8,600, instead of $7,200 now. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: Allow married couples to choose to file  
returns as if single, increasing their standard deduction. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: Allow married couples with taxable income  
below $95,000 an itemized deduction of up to $4,350. 

</P>
<P>
 *CAPITAL GAINS   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Cut top rate for most investments held at  
least a year from 20 percent to 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: No provision.  
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: No provision.  

</P>
<P>
 *ALTERNATIVE MINIMUM TAX   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Ensure personal credits do not cause  
middle-class people to become subject to the tax and eventually 
repealing the AMT. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: Ensure personal credits do not cause  
middle-class people to become subject to the AMT. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: Similar to Senate GOP.  

</P>
<P>
 *ESTATE TAX   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Phases down and eventually repeals tax on  
inheritances. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: Gradually reduce tax rates and increase  
exemption to $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: Accelerates phase-in of $1 million exemption,  
up from $650,000 now. 

</P>
<P>
 *RETIREMENT   	
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans: Increased contribution to some employee  
benefit plans and vesting in pensions after five years instead of 
three. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Republicans: Increase individual retirement account  
contribution limits to $5,000 and create new Roth 401(k) in which 
after-tax contributions are withdrawn tax-free. Eliminate income 
limits on all IRAs. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats: Offer small businesses tax credit to start  
pension plans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
