<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Uruguay in Soccer Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- Uruguay has earned a reputation as a  
giant-killer on the way to the finals of the Copa America. Now they 
play for the title against the biggest giant of them all: Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	In emotion if not technique, Sunday's battle for the South  
American championship is about as good as it gets. 
</P>
<P>
	On one side, perennial favorite Brazil is the odds-on pick to  
repeat as Copa America champs. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-time World Cup champions, led by Ronaldo and Rivaldo,  
are undefeated and have 14 goals in five games. 
</P>
<P>
	Dida, the goalie, has allowed just two goals, fewest in the  
tournament, and has saved a pair of penalty kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Uruguay is devoid of international stars and barely sneaked into  
the second round by beating Ecuador after losses to Argentina and 
Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	But the youngsters, built around the core of the junior team  
that finished second in the 1997 Under 20 world championship in 
Malaysia, beat host Parguay in the quarterfinals in a shootout, 
then beat Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	For coach Victor Pua, the final is a classic matchup of Brazil's  
``talent and experience'' against his team's ``youth, dreams and 
desire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Uruguay has won the Copa America 14 times, including the first  
one in 1916, and is tied with Argentina for the most titles. Brazil 
has won it five times, only once away from home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
