<DOCNO> APW19990717.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Phone Call Led to Search for JFK Jr. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It started with a telephone call from a friend  
of one of America's most famous families: A plane carrying John F. 
Kennedy Jr., the anxious caller said, was past due at the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	With that report, made about 2:15 a.m. Saturday to the Coast  
Guard station in Woods Hole, Mass., the military hierarchy sprang 
into action and started a desperate search for the son of a former 
commander-in-chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews in Woods Hole contacted the Federal Aviation  
Administration, according to Coast Guard Rear Admiral Richard 
Larrabee. The FAA, charged with supervising the nation's air space, 
in turn started calling airports and flight-tracking centers up and 
down the East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's plane, a Piper Saratoga II HP carrying him, his wife,  
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, and her sister Lauren, had left 
Fairfield, N.J., Friday evening. It was due into the airport at 
Martha's Vineyard, Mass., well before midnight. Airport officials 
said it never arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	As it called its own personnel, the FAA also placed call to the  
Air Force Rescue Coordination Center at Langley Air Force Base in 
Hampton, Va., the elite unit that coordinates searches throughout 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	By 3:30 a.m., Larrabee said, the unit called back to the Coast  
Guard and reported a satellite had received a signal from an 
emergency locator beacon over land on the northern end of Long 
Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Larrabee said a boat was sent to the area but did not find  
anything during a three-hour search. 
</P>
<P>
	At 7:30 a.m., Larrabee said ``a more aggressive search'' was  
launched. A Coast Guard jet was dispatched to the skies over Long 
Island Sound. Two Coast Guard helicopters were launched to search 
between Martha's Vineyard and Montauk, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	An Air Force C-130 was transformed into an aerial command post  
and sent to southern Long Island. Within hours, 15 more small 
planes manned by volunteers from the Civil Air Patrol, the Air 
Force auxiliary organization, also were buzzing over the coastline. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1 p.m., the search parties zeroed in on a spot 17 miles  
southwest of Martha's Vineyard, after swimmers found a suitcase 
bearing Lauren Bessette's luggage tag floating in the surf off 
Philbin Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon said the sizable search had nothing to do with  
Kennedy's status as the only son of the late President John F. 
Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We treat all the searches the same,'' said Lt. Col. Steve  
Roark, an official at the Air Force rescue center. ``There is no 
difference between celebrity and noncelebrity. Our job is for all 
the citizens of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also defended the four-hour time lag between receiving  
a report of the missing plane and launching a more intensive 
search. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does take time to research. We look at possible other  
landing sites ... rather than just sending out aircraft 
willy-nilly,'' Roark said. 
</P>
<P>
	Larrabee said rescuers were hampered by the fact that Kennedy  
did not file a flight plan for his trip, which was not required. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point we didn't have any better information because we  
did not have a flight plan,'' Larrabee said, recalling the early 
morning hours. ``We had a time of departure but did not have any 
other good information, so we found ourselves searching a very 
large area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larrabee said the searchers planned to continue until they found  
the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather is really not a factor,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	A federal research vessel capable of undersea searches sailed to  
the scene from Montauk, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rude, pronounced rue-dee, surveys the ocean floor for the  
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Towing a 
side-scanning sensor shaped like a torpedo, it can examine a swath 
of the ocean bottom 600 feet wide as it moves slowly along. 
</P>
<P>
	The waters of the search area are relatively shallow, ranging  
from 10 to 100 feet, officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 20:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Networks Focusing on Kennedy Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Television networks set aside normal weekend  
programming Saturday to maintain a constant vigil during the grim 
search for John F. Kennedy Jr.'s missing plane. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC, CBS, NBC and the cable news networks beamed continuous  
coverage of the story from the moment the story broke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be on the air at least until we know the fate of John F.  
Kennedy Jr.,'' promised CBS's Dan Rather Saturday afternoon, after 
he had already been broadcasting for more than four hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Hager, NBC's chief aviation correspondent, broke the story  
at 8:06 a.m. EDT. CBS and ABC followed within a few minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Coverage of the LPGA's Big Apple Golf Tournament and of a  
women's basketball game were bumped from NBC to sister cable 
station CNBC. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC was scheduled to show the third round of the British Open  
but instead stayed with the breaking story, switching coverage to 
Disney-owned ESPN. The Major League Soccer All-Star game was 
switched to ESPN2. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS pre-empted coverage of the Ameritech Senior Open, which was  
scheduled to air for two hours Saturday afternoon. In lieu of its 
scheduled broadcast, the network offered affiliates a 15-minute 
highlight package, said Brian Fitzgerald, tournament director. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an unfortunate situation,'' Fitzgerald said. ``All three  
networks made the decision to go with coverage of the search.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers were just as aggressive to respond. The Chicago  
Sun-Times published an ``Extra Edition'' of its Sunday newspaper 
with the banner headline: ``JFK JR.'S PLANE MISSING.'' The edition 
was circulating on the streets Saturday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're tearing up page one and re-designing it,'' said Ray  
Quintanilla, afternoon editor of the Chicago Tribune. ``This is the 
sort of story that warrants it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times is dedicating at least one full page to the  
Kennedy story in the Sunday edition, said Carolyn Lee, an assistant 
managing editor. But the paper has not added extra editions, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Post is adding 16 pages to the Sunday edition. The  
Post is expanding the paper from 112 pages to 128. More than 24 
pages cover the Kennedy story. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Globe, and Boston.com -- the Globe's Website -- planned  
coverage for Kennedy story. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, pages A12 through A20 will be devoted to  
Kennedy,'' said Michael Larkin, assistant managing editor for the 
Boston Globe's Sunday edition. Boston.com said it is putting 
virtually all of the Globe's stories on its website. 
</P>
<P>
	Others hungry for news turned to Internet sites, reading  
stories, watching live coverage and adding their own comments in 
virtual chat rooms and bulletin boards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web sites of MSNBC, ABC, CBS, CNN, Fox and The Associated  
Press all relayed their live audio and video coverage on the 
search, in addition to print stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Central, the Web site of the Arizona Republic newspaper,  
supplemented its coverage with a bulletin board where readers could 
post their reactions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web sites of networks ABC, MSNBC, CBS and Fox also provided  
live chat sessions where people could post questions and comments 
on the drama. 
</P>
<P>
	On television, Rather was the first major network anchor to get  
on the air after the news broke. NBC's Tom Brokaw and ABC's Peter 
Jennings also arrived to take the helm of their network's coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	For the broadcasters, the story's unfolding was painfully slow.  
Each morsel of information -- a potential radar sighting of the 
plane, a washed-up piece of luggage, spotting of airplane wreckage 
-- contributed to a picture becoming clearer in the same way a 
motorist spots something in the distance. 
</P>
<P>
	At times, the information was uncertain, such as early  
conflicting reports that Kennedy had been accompanied by a flight 
instructor on his plane. Rather, in particular, repeatedly urged 
caution against jumping to conclusions based on sketchy 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	Others were more aggressive. ABC presented a graphic of a plane  
pitching into the ocean, with specific altitude figures, before 
confirmation of a crash. The network said its information on the 
plane's possible fate came from ``aviation sources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telecasts grew more somber as no good news emerged. ABC's  
Charles Gibson, stationed outside the Kennedy compound in Hyannis, 
Mass., noted that ``the faces of those coming out do not look very 
hopeful to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the anchors, the story seemed particularly poignant. Not  
only did they each start their careers in the 1960s when the 
Kennedy legacy loomed largest, they were fellow members of the New 
York media establishment with Kennedy, publisher of George 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather told of running into Kennedy in coffee shops in  
Manhattan, and Kennedy attended last winter's release party for 
Brokaw's book, ``The Greatest Generation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Phone Call Led to Search for JFK Jr. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It started with a telephone call from a friend  
of one of America's most famous families: A plane carrying John F. 
