<HEADLINE> Va. Tourists React to JFK Jr. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- On a hot, muggy summer afternoon in July,  
visitors at the hillside grave of President John F. Kennedy voiced 
amazement and sadness Saturday over the disappearance of his son's 
small plane near the Massachusetts island of Martha's Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Reid of Chicago said she was ``astonished'' to learn that  
John F. Kennedy Jr. was missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy's wife, Carolyn, and her sister are believed to be the  
other passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just really sad,'' Reid said. ``It's like there's some  
sort of a curse on the Kennedy family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many tourists at Arlington National Cemetery said they were  
unaware of the missing aircraft. Others said they learned of the 
event while visiting the Kennedy family memorial. President Kennedy 
and his wife, Jacqueline, are buried near the graves of their first 
child, an unnamed daughter stillborn in 1956, and an infant son, 
Patrick, who died three days after birth in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people have been asking about him; wanting to know  
what's going on,'' said Tamika Wallace, a visitor center employee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just heard about the missing plane thirty seconds ago...it's  
shocking,'' said Alex Hoffman, a visitor from New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Arlington National Cemetery attracts thousands of visitors  
daily. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
