<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Rep. Forbes Joining Democrats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUOGUE, N.Y. (AP) -- A Republican lawmaker switched allegiance to  
the Democrats Saturday, the first such defection since the GOP took 
control of Congress five years ago. He drew praise from President 
Clinton for having the ``courage to change'' and scorn from the GOP 
for placing ``ego ahead of principle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Michael Forbes, who represents the eastern tip of New  
York's Long Island, told reporters at his home that the Republican 
Party ``has become an angry, narrow-minded, intolerant and uncaring 
majority, incapable of governing at all, much less from the center, 
and tone-deaf to the concerns of a vast majority of Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While he was first elected to the House in 1994 as a supporter  
of the conservative ``Contract with America,'' Forbes clashed 
numerous times with the GOP leadership. His most prominent break 
came in 1997, when he refused to support then-Rep. Newt Gingrich 
for re-election as speaker, citing concerns over an ethics probe. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, he found himself briefly near the center of power  
in the House when it appeared last year that Rep. Bob Livingston 
would succeed Gingrich as speaker. Livingston quit Congress 
unexpectedly, though, and Forbes' political stock plummeted 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The defection provides an important psychological lift for  
Democrats who hope to regain control of the House in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	With Forbes' announcement, Republicans will hold 222 seats in  
the 435-member House, with 211 Democrats and an independent who 
usually votes with the Democrats. A seat is vacant because of the 
death Thursday of Rep. George Brown, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who has shown a strong independent streak, said the GOP  
has become ``a captive of extremists,'' and he said the Democratic 
Party is more open. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republican Party over the last 4 1/2 years has been defined  
through the actions of its extremists in the House of 
Representatives,'' Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sadly, there's no room in the Republican Party in Congress for  
moderates like myself,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he knew Forbes ``made a hard choice, but ... the  
right choice'' and is ``joining a party that welcomes independent 
thinking and the courage to change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From Vice President Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic  
presidential nomination, came recognition of Forbes as ``a man of 
principle and integrity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Praise flowed from the White House even though, as Republicans  
noted, Forbes recently endorsed Texas' Republican Gov. George W. 
Bush for president in 2000 and voted to impeach Clinton on all four 
of the charges brought by the House Judiciary Committee last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand your anger, but the Republicans in Washington  
aren't reflecting your values or concerns,'' Forbes told one 
constituent who complained about his switch. ``I am the same person 
that I was yesterday and the day before that and the year before 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans believe Forbes is ``obviously putting his personal  
ego ahead of principle and ahead of the interests of his district, 
which is solidly Republican,'' said Jill Schroeder, a spokeswoman 
for the GOP campaign committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton won 51 percent of the vote in Forbes' district in 1996,  
compared with 36 percent for Republican Bob Dole. The vote four 
years earlier was 40 percent for President Bush and 38 percent for 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' decision followed a series of private conversations over  
several weeks with Democratic House members from New York and the 
House's top Democrat, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes also met privately at the White House with Clinton at one  
point. The meeting with the president was unannounced at the time, 
and officials said the conversations with Gephardt occurred away 
from his Capitol office to avoid detection. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, 47, defeated a Democrat to win his seat in 1994, one of  
more than 70 GOP first-termers who helped usher a Republican 
majority into the House for the first time in 40 years. Between 
1961 and 1995, when Forbes took office, Democrats had represented 
the district for 26 of those 34 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Five House Democrats switched to the GOP in 1995. In the Senate,  
Richard Shelby of Alabama and Colorado's Ben Nighthorse Campbell 
also switched from the Democrats in the last few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes is the second Republican to leave his party in less than  
a week. On Wednesday, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., running at the back 
of the pack in the race for the GOP presidential nomination, became 
an independent. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	AP reporter Dave Espo contributed to this story from Washington.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
