<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jeb Bush Criticized Over Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Just days after calling for tough  
ethical standards for his new administration, Gov. Jeb Bush 
accepted three $400 tickets to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides say the tickets were gifts from an old friend, and  
fit in under an exception to his ethics policy -- gifts from 
personal friends who don't have business pending before state. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Florida Democratic Party charged that by going to the  
Super Bowl in Miami for free, the Republican compromised the 
standards he set for himself and his administration when he took 
office earlier in January promising to ``raise the bar'' on ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	State law only prohibits public officials from accepting gifts  
from lobbyists over $100. Bush said he wanted a higher standard and 
limited his administration to gifts worth $25 or less if they are 
from lobbyists. 
</P>
<P>
	``As it turns out, the governor's policy was in place for all of  
nine days before he handed himself the first exemption,'' said 
Democratic Party chairman Charles Whitehead. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokesman Cory Tilley said Friday that the tickets, from  
Miami attorney and longtime Bush buddy Dean Colson, fall under the 
exception area. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor didn't pay for the tickets because Dean Colson is  
a close personal friend and not a lobbyist,'' Tilley said. ``The 
governor's staff and the governor should be able to receive gifts 
from personal friends if the individual doesn't have something 
before the governor that he has to make a decision on, and Mr. 
Colson didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colson was a member of the Miami Super Bowl host committee.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush took his two sons to the Jan. 31 game at Pro Player Stadium  
between the Denver Broncos and Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	Tilley also argued that a showcase event like the Super Bowl  
isn't just a personal trip -- it's almost like a state function the 
governor should attend. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the biggest economic development events in  
South Florida,'' Tilley said. ``If the governor wasn't there, it 
would have been strange.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
