<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Capt. Charts New Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Eileen Collins likes to use a little  
model of a space shuttle when explaining to her littlest fan where 
she'll be sitting when Columbia blasts off this week. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Bridget responds with a ``Yippee!'' What she doesn't  
know, can't know at age 3 1/2, is that Mommy is about to become the 
first woman to lead a crew into space. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's first female commander laughs as she recalls how her  
daughter once asked: ``Mommy, have you ever been to the moon?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think she understands the big picture,'' says Collins.  
``I don't think she knows that everybody's mother doesn't fly in 
space or command a space shuttle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday -- coincidentally, the 30th anniversary of man's first  
moon landing -- Collins will chart a new course for women when she 
slides into the front left seat of Columbia and takes the controls 
at liftoff. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first time in 95 space shuttle launches -- 126  
counting Mercury, Gemini, Apollo and Skylab -- that a woman is at 
the helm. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42-year-old Air Force colonel will be responsible for four  
other astronauts, three of them older men. 
</P>
<P>
	She'll also be responsible for the heftiest and one of the  
priciest shuttle payloads ever: NASA's 25-ton, $1.5 billion Chandra 
X-ray Observatory, on a scientific par with the Hubble Space 
Telescope. The price tag for the entire Chandra project, from 
development through five years of orbital operation: $2.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Is Collins nervous? No.  
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to have the attitude that, 'I am confident enough  
to handle anything,''' says the former test pilot, who has logged 
more than 5,000 hours in 30 types of aircraft. ``I have a lot of 
faith in God. That's another thing I think that goes a long way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Does she feel the pressure? You bet. But she doesn't dwell on  
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time my brain starts going in that direction, I stop  
myself and go, 'Eileen, you're not focusing on the mission. Focus 
on the mission.''' 
</P>
<P>
	And she has, for 1 1/2 years.  
</P>
<P>
	Her promotion from shuttle pilot to shuttle commander was  
announced by Hillary Rodham Clinton at a White House ceremony in 
March 1998, a few months after NASA gave her the prestigious 
five-day mission to deliver the telescope to orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of young girls who need to see Eileen in the  
commander's seat achieving her dreams,'' says Air Force Lt. Col. 
Catherine ``Cady'' Coleman, 38, who is on Collins' crew. ``Not so 
that they can all be astronauts, because then the line to go to 
space would be way too long, but because they realize that they can 
achieve their dreams if they work for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second of four children, she grew up in public housing in  
Elmira, N.Y. Her father recalls how he'd take the family to a local 
air field to watch gliders and small planes; they could afford 
little else. 
</P>
<P>
	Good at math, Collins considered teaching. Her father suggested  
accounting. But the images of gliders and planes stuck. She took 
odd jobs to pay for flying lessons and, with the help of loans and 
scholarships, aimed for an Air Force career. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins graduated from Syracuse University with a bachelor's  
degree in math and economics in 1978, the same year NASA accepted 
its first female astronauts. With her sights on space, she trained 
as an Air Force pilot, then served as a T-38 and C-141 instructor 
pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	After teaching math and instructing T-41 pilots at the U.S. Air  
Force Academy, Collins became only the second woman to enter Air 
Force Test Pilot School. That same year, 1989, she applied to 
become an astronaut. A year later, NASA chose her as its first 
female shuttle pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1995, Collins made her debut as the  
second-in-command pilot of Discovery. The afterglow was 
short-lived; one month after the mission, someone threatened to 
kill her at a parade planned in her honor in Elmira. She skipped 
the parade. The perpetrator was never caught. 
</P>
<P>
	She took a six-week maternity leave following Bridget's birth in  
November 1995, then flew again as a shuttle pilot to Mir 1 1/2 years 
later. By then, strangers in restaurants no longer asked for her 
autograph. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know this is going to start happening again,'' she says.  
``But it will pass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, though, the spotlight is on.  
</P>
<P>
	Women in aerospace and aviation will converge on Kennedy Space  
Center for Collins' middle-of-the-night launch. Sally Ride, who 
became the first American woman in space in 1983, will be there, 
too, with a dual interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Ride's former husband, astronaut Steven Hawley, 47, will rocket  
into orbit with Collins. He was on the astronaut-selection board 
that chose Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this is a new and important step, in some sense it's  
a natural evolution,'' says Hawley. He points to the numbers as 
evidence: Of the 283 people who have flown on U.S. spacecraft, 32 
have been women. (NASA does not count the the three rookies killed 
aboard Challenger in 1986.) Of NASA's current 118 astronauts, 29 
are women. Of NASA's 40 shuttle pilots, three are women. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's egalitarian boss, Daniel Goldin, is unfazed: ``Eileen  
Collins is the commander. So what's the news?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force Lt. Col. Pamela Melroy can't think of anyone better  
suited. 
</P>
<P>
	``She really is technically extremely good, but there's a lot  
more that goes into it than that,'' says Melroy, 37, who will fly 
as a shuttle pilot early next year. ``It's her personality. She's 
such a nice person, just easygoing, very friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins' nurturing side often shows.  
</P>
<P>
	At a practice countdown last month, Collins tried to deflect  
attention toward her crew, in particular 49-year-old French 
astronaut Michel Tognini. It didn't work. Collins still got the 
last question, but she made sure no one left until Tognini had a 
chance to speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins cites her two jobs -- being an astronaut and being a  
mother -- as equally difficult, yet equally rewarding. In fact, she 
says, being a parent has made her a more sensitive commander and 
actually decreased her level of stress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that she has a young daughter, Bridget, that has kind of  
rounded everything out,'' observes her father, Jim Collins, 72, a 
U.S. Postal Service clerk in Rochester, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Though very proud, he refuses to take credit. ``Everything that  
Eileen is today, she has earned,'' he says. ``She was born with 
this desire to be a success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Collins does credit her parents, as well as her husband Pat  
Youngs, a 41-year-old pilot for Delta Air Lines. She also relies on 
her own high level of energy and a low need for sleep, plus a 
wonderful nanny. 
</P>
<P>
	In the male-dominated world of aerospace, not everyone has  
embraced Collins' success. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronaut Coleman has had to defend her commander whenever she  
chats with crusty old-timers at small airports. ``They're not going 
to let her land it, are they?'' the men ask. ``I certainly hope so, 
since she's sitting in the front seat,'' Coleman replies, with a 
laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Even crewmate Hawley admits that not every man in the astronaut  
corps would like reporting to a woman. Aware of this, the NASA 
official who assembled Collins' crew says he purposely chose 
open-minded men. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins doesn't pay much mind.  
</P>
<P>
	``My attitude toward that stuff is, I will be part of making an  
evolutionary change. And it's going to happen.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 10:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer McGee Returns After Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG GROVE, Ill. (AP) -- On the night Jerry McGee had malignant  
tumors removed from his mouth and neck, his wife sat with her 
husband until dawn, not sure if he was going to make it. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend, Jill McGee is back at her husband's side, walking  
the course with him as he makes a triumphant return to the Senior 
PGA Tour at the Ameritech Senior Open, less than four months after 
surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels fantastic,'' McGee said, his voice catching. ``I knew  
it was going to be a very, very emotional week. I don't know how 
many times I've almost broken down out here. I'm definitely happy 
to be back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGee is looking forward to his 56th birthday on Wednesday. He  
hasn't regained the 30 pounds he lost after 6 1/2 weeks of radiation, 
and his stamina is nowhere near what it used to be. He's the first 
to admit his game isn't really ready, and in Friday's first round, 
he shot a 44 on the back nine to finish at 6-over 78. 
</P>
<P>
	But his score doesn't matter. He's alive, and that's better than  
any trophy he could ever win. 
</P>
<P>
	``Emotional. It was very emotional,'' Jill McGee said after her  
husband's round Friday, tears filling her eyes. ``For the first 
time, I didn't care how he played. I was just glad he made it 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was last winter that McGee felt a lump on the left side of  
his neck, and he knew right away something was wrong. He'd been a 
heavy smoker for 20 years, going through 3 1/2 packs a day before 
quitting eight or nine years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The first doctor he saw told him the lump wasn't malignant, but  
he wanted to remove it anyway. That didn't feel right to McGee, so 
he went to see Dr. Eugene Myers at the University of Pittsburgh 
Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Cancer, Myers told him on March 17. There were two tumors, the  
one in his neck and another on his tongue, and both needed to be 
removed immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	McGee balked, asking if there was any way he could wait until  
November so he could finish the season and keep his spot on the 
all-time money list. The top 70 on the list get priority at 
tournaments, and McGee began the season at No. 53. He's currently 
57th. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `Sure, Jerry, we can wait. But you won't be here in  
November,'' McGee said, his eyes widening at the memory. ``It was 
like someone hit me over the head with a sledgehammer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On March 24, McGee had surgery. The tumors were removed, along  
with the lymph nodes on the left side of his neck to prevent the 
cancer from spreading. Then came the radiation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever had a canker sore? I had like 500 of them,'' he said. ``I  
told my doctor it was strep throat times 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For weeks, all he could eat were soft, mushy eggs. He lost his  
saliva glands, and he still can't taste what he's eating. And he 
lost so much weight some friends didn't recognize him when they saw 
him in the locker room this week. 
</P>
<P>
	But within a few weeks, McGee was back on the golf course.  
</P>
<P>
	``The thought of hoping to play again did keep me going, but I  
didn't know if I could,'' he said. ``I thought I would play again 
in my prayers. And I had a lot of people praying. Prayers work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every day, there was a call or a card from a player, PGA  
official, caddie or tournament organizer. McGee and his family were 
overwhelmed by the support, and part of his reason for wanting to 
play this season was to say thank you. 
</P>
<P>
	He wanted to come back three weeks ago for the Senior Players  
Championship, but his body wasn't ready. He still isn't back to 
full strength, but his return has been a cause for celebration on 
the tour. Several other players on the Senior Tour, including 
Arnold Palmer, have been diagnosed with cancer in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately we're all getting to the stage in life agewise  
where we find out these things,'' said David Graham, co-leader 
after the first round. ``It's great to have him back. ... Whether 
he plays well or not may be irrelevant. It's nice to know one of us 
has come through this so well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGee can't walk more than a few feet without someone coming  
over to say hello and tell him how good it is to see him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, it's good to see YOU!'' McGee replies.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost too bad it took something this bad to happen to me  
to see all the love in this world,'' he said. ``Every shot I used 
to hit was a life-or-death situation and that's not the way you 
should live life. I think that's why the pro in the sky decided to 
straighten me out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cancer is gone, doctors have told McGee, but he still needs  
checkups every two to three months. And it will be at least five 
years before he can even think about the word ``cure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But each day is a step toward that. And this weekend, well, it's  
just something very, very special. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't won yet on the Senior Tour, but this is definitely  
my first victory,'' he said. ``I'm not going to get a trophy, but 
it's definitely a victory.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 21:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers' Burnitz Breaks Bone in Hand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- All-Star outfielder Jeromy Burnitz will be out  
at least three weeks after breaking a bone in his right hand during 
the Brewers' game against Kansas City on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz was hit in the fourth inning by a pitch from the Royals'  
Jose Rosado. He stayed in the game but was replaced by Geoff 
Jenkins in the top of the sixth inning after Milwaukee took a 9-1 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays revealed a non-displaced fracture of the fifth metacarpal  
bone in his hand. Burnitz's hand was placed in a splint and will be 
reevaluated on Sunday, but the fracture will keep Burnitz out of 
the lineup for at least three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough break, but we've got some guys who are ready to  
step in there,'' manager Phil Garner said. ``We don't like to lose 
Burnie, but we won't hang our heads and quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers likely will place Burnitz on the 15-day disabled  
list when pitcher Rocky Coppinger, who was acquired from Baltimore 
on Friday, reports to the team. That could be as early as Sunday, 
when the Brewers open a three-game home series against the Chicago 
White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz started for the National League in Tuesday's All-Star  
game and hit an RBI double. He also finished second to Ken Griffey 
Jr. in the home run-hitting contest. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been having another great year, but a lot of guys in our  
lineup are swinging the bat well now,'' Garner said after Milwaukee 
racked up 17 hits in its 11-3 win over the Royals. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner said Burnitz will be replaced in the Brewers' starting  
lineup by Alex Ochoa, who hit two home runs Saturday night. Ochoa 
and Jenkins have been splitting time in left field. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz was 0-for-2 with a strikeout Saturday. Burnitz has 26  
home runs and 73 RBIs this season while hitting .275. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
