<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Van de Velde Leads Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- Perfect.  
</P>
<P>
	All these overworked, overmatched, overwrought pros getting  
their brains beat out at the British Open complain nonstop about 
the Mickey Mouse course and conditions. So guess who turns up atop 
the leaderboard heading into the final round? 
</P>
<P>
	The pro from Disneyland, of course.  
</P>
<P>
	By way of Paris.  
</P>
<P>
	``I test all the rides,'' Frenchman Jean Van de Velde said,  
going along with the gag, ``and walk around with all the 
characters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most people don't know there are topflight golfers in France,  
let alone a topflight course attached to Disneyland outside Paris. 
And that includes more than a few of Van de Velde's countrymen. 
</P>
<P>
	But all that could change by close of light Sunday if the  
33-year-old former Masters champion (that's the Roma Masters, not 
THE Masters) can play one more round nearly as courageously as the 
last two he's already thrown at the devilishly difficult Carnoustie 
Golf Links. 
</P>
<P>
	``What would the reaction back home be?'' someone asked Van de  
Velde. ``Would there be dancing in the streets?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He considered the possibility for the briefest of moments.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's only 300,000 people playing golf in the country,'' Van  
de Velde said, ``so I hope they will all be in Paris tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is obviously an entertaining man, but he came here to play  
golf, not tell jokes. And besides, there are larger questions to be 
answered. 
</P>
<P>
	First, even starting the final day with a five-stroke lead, can  
Van de Velde stay ahead of a pursuing pack that includes Tiger 
Woods and former British champions Justin Leonard and Greg Norman? 
And if he does, will that victory be regarded as a fluke? 
</P>
<P>
	After all, this is supposed to be the toughest venue of the  
toughest championship in golf, and all five of the previous Open 
champions Carnoustie has produced rank among the game's greatest: 
Tommy Armour (1931); Henry Cotton (1937); Ben Hogan (1953); Gary 
Player (1968); and Tom Watson (1975). 
</P>
<P>
	And considering some of the weird bounces and breaks that have  
been dealt out this week in the wind, rain and rough, there would 
be temptation to write a Van de Velde victory off as nothing more 
than a generous alignment of his planets. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike first-round leader and relative unknown Rodney  
Pampling -- who followed up a 71 with an 86 and was last seen 
booking a flight to Australia after missing the cut -- third-round 
leader and relative unknown Van de Velde has shown real staying 
power. Every time a bogey threatened his momentum Saturday, he 
pulled a birdie out of his hat. That surprised everyone but him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody can beat anybody, and that's the beauty of the  
game,'' he said. ``You're out there and you're playing with Mr. 
Norman or Mr. Woods or whoever and still, at the end of the day, 
you're going to beat them by one'' -- and here Van de Velde paused -- 
``maybe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is a longshot in every sense of the word, a one-time winner  
on the European tour who had to play his way into the Open in a 
qualifying tournament, a kid who grew up in a country that once 
cared as little for golf as the Disney characters Van de Velde now 
works for as a frontman. 
</P>
<P>
	He discovered his life's work as a 6 1/2-year-old, tired of playing  
at the beach where his family vacationed every year, near Biarritz, 
France. He watched golfers walk past the family's summer home and 
nagged his parents to let him play until they finally gave in. 
</P>
<P>
	He had precious few role models. Arnaud Massey, the only  
Frenchman ever to win the British Open, did it 92 years ago. The 
last time one of his countrymen even led this tournament was 1964, 
when Jean Garaialde did before eventually fading to 13th. 
</P>
<P>
	Small wonder then, that when Van de Velde got serious about the  
game, the man he emulated was the swashbuckling Seve Ballesteros, 
who lived some 100 miles across the border in Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	By 20, Van de Velde was good enough to turn pro. Now, more than  
a dozen years later, he has his first chance to set the world on 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you tee off here, it's because you deserve to be here.  
That's the first thing. If you believe you can make it through, 
then, you know, it might happen. If you don't, then it never will 
happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always a first time. Even the big guys,'' he said,  
``they had to do it once.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
