<DOCNO> APW19990717.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 00:20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 GOP Presidential Hopefuls in Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While Texas Gov. George W. Bush sets  
fund-raising records, four of his Republican opponents are in debt 
months before the first primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Through June 30, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,  
conservative activist Gary Bauer, former Vice President Dan Quayle 
and publisher Steve Forbes all reported owing more money than they 
held in their campaign bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer and Quayle are each $500,000 in debt.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bush raised a record $37 million and has $30 million  
in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, a millionaire who is largely financing his own campaign,  
can simply write a personal check and pay off his $221,555 debt. 
The other three candidates are in a more precarious position. But 
officials at each campaign say they have a plan for financing their 
efforts until they begin receiving matching funds from the 
government next January. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer and Quayle have met the threshold for receiving the funds,  
collecting $5,000 in contributions of $250 or less in 20 different 
states. Alexander has yet to be certified to receive the federal 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on what they have raised so far, Bauer is to receive $2.5  
million and Quayle $1.8 million in federal funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have the money required to get out Dan Quayle's  
message of principled conservative leadership,'' Quayle spokesman 
Jonathan Baron said. ``Ultimately, that's what activists care most 
about. There's no question George W. Bush has created an extremely 
tight fund-raising environment, but ultimately ideas will 
triumph.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, like Bush, has said he will not accept matching funds,  
freeing him from spending limits the others will have to abide by. 
</P>
<P>
	With Bush vacuuming up so much money, it will be even more  
difficult for the other candidates to raise enough to pay their 
debts and continue their campaigns through next winter's Iowa 
caucuses and New Hampshire primary, said Herbert Alexander, 
professor emeritus of political science at the University of 
Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who know that they're in debt would have to be  
especially dedicated to their candidates to continue at this 
point,'' he said. ``They probably have already hit the cream of 
their support. Now it's going to be harder and harder. Six months 
is an awfully long time to stick in there and accrue even more 
debt. I don't see how a candidate can really do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Sen. John McCain and former American Red  
Cross President Elizabeth Dole both reported having more than 
enough money in the bank to pay off their debts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is another sign that this race is heading toward  
a two-person contest between Governor Bush and Elizabeth Dole,'' 
Dole spokesman Ari Fleischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye toward next month's Iowa straw poll, the other  
candidates said they will have enough money to continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have to do is keep current with our payables and  
continue to raise money,'' said Brian Kennedy, campaign manager for 
Alexander, the former Tennessee governor who earlier laid off staff 
in order to conserve funds. ``We'll be able to fully compete in 
Iowa and New Hampshire and the other early contests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander raised $2.5 million through June 30, and was $143,373  
in debt. At this period four years ago, he had raised three times 
that amount, $7.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Bauer and Quayle are relying heavily on expensive direct  
mail. Quayle spent $1.9 million on fund raising, 57 percent of the 
$3.4 million he has spent on his campaign during the first six 
months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Between April and June, Bauer spent $475,179 on direct mail, his  
largest individual expenditure. He also spent $443,733 on salaries. 
Overall, Bauer spent $2.2 million during the three months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaign's happening fast now,'' campaign manager Frank  
Cannon said. ``We're actively setting up organizations and hiring 
people. We're competing, and that costs money.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
