<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lines of scattered thunderstorms extended across the Great  
Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the Gulf Coast states on Saturday. 
Temperatures hit record highs in the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	By late afternoon, storms and showers were scattered from Texas  
across the Mississippi and Ohio valleys into the Great Lakes, and 
on into eastern Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong storms moved across southeastern Michigan, and funnel  
clouds were reported around the middle of the day over northern 
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those stronger storms also spread into parts of Indiana,  
Ohio, western Pennsylvania and western New York state. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of that rain was expected to move eastward into northern  
New England during the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahead of the wet weather, a heat wave covered much of the  
Northeast on Saturday. Harrisburg, Pa., tied its record for the 
date with a high of 100, and Boston tied its record at 98, the 
National Weather Service reported. Temperatures hit records of 97 
at Portland, Maine; Burlington, Vt.; and Concord, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms also developed during the afternoon along the  
coast of the Gulf of Mexico, from southern Texas across Louisiana, 
Mississippi and Alabama into most of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Widely scattered thunderstorms also developed during the  
afternoon along the Appalachians, from Georgia into central 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Southwest, showers and a few thunderstorms formed during  
the afternoon across eastern Arizona, wide areas of New Mexico and 
parts of Colorado, with a few areas of rain spreading eastward into 
Kansas and the Oklahoma Panhandle and northward into Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, an area of locally heavy rain and thunderstorms  
formed over the Dakotas during the afternoon and moved eastward 
toward Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers also moved across western Washington state and from  
northern Utah through Idaho into western Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 33 at Stanley, Idaho, to the high of 100 Harrisburg, 
Pa. The lowest wind chill was 27 at Sexton, Ore., and the highest 
heat index by early afternoon was 107 at Biloxi, Miss. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
