<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Agency's Funding Nixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A group that helps homeless people has  
lost federal funding because its application for assistance asks 
too many questions about religion, county officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	In the application form, Operation Blessing asked whether  
applicants considered themselves saved from eternal damnation 
because they are observant Christians. The agency also asked 
whether people needing aid believed they will go to heaven. 
</P>
<P>
	About two years ago, Operation Blessing applied for and received  
a $50,000 federal grant. It used the money to house, clothe and 
feed the homeless. The group also helped pay utility bills and 
mortgage payments to prevent homelessness. 
</P>
<P>
	County officials who manage the grant money informed Operation  
Blessing's officials in May that asking about an applicant's faith 
is considered a violation of federal regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Group officials wonder why their grant was approved in the first  
place since they provided a sample of the application form. 
</P>
<P>
	Operation Blessings board president Martin Rasmussen said the  
message seemed to him to be that ``Christian organizations should 
not work with the government on helping people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 02:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Ruling Allows Late-Term Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- State attorneys say they will appeal a  
federal court ruling that blocks Virginia from enforcing its ban on 
a type of late-term abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Robert E. Payne on Friday ruled that the ban  
is unconstitutional, saying it is too vague and infringes upon a 
woman's right to an abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Mark L. Earley disagreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We still believe Virginia's statute is well-reasoned, legally  
sound and crafted narrowly enough to pass constitutional muster,'' 
Earley said. ``It is designed for one purpose: to ban this 
disturbing procedure which, by all accounts, borders on 
infanticide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payne issued a permanent injunction barring enforcement of the  
law, which took effect on July 1, 1998, and bans the procedure that 
opponents call ``partial-birth abortion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the procedure, a doctor delivers part of a fetus, destroys  
it, then removes the dead fetus from the mother's body. The law 
provided an exception to save the life of the mother, but did not 
make any exception to protect the mother's health. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the procedure say it is never medically necessary  
and can be banned without violating court rulings that say women 
have a right to have abortions. Abortion doctors, however, say the 
procedure is sometimes the best option for protecting the health of 
pregnant women. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne said the law ``infringes upon the fundamental right to  
choose an abortion because it imposes an undue burden on that right 
and because it contains no health exception and an inadequate life 
exception.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Planned Parenthood Advocates of Virginia and a group of abortion  
providers challenged the law shortly after it was passed. They 
claimed the law was so broad that it could be construed as banning 
many types of conventional abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Violation of the law was a misdemeanor punishable by up to one  
year in jail and a $2,500 fine. A doctor also could lose his 
medical license. 
</P>
<P>
	Bans on the procedure have been blocked or severely limited in  
19 of the 20 states where they have been challenged, the New 
York-based Center for Reproductive Law and Policy said. Abortion 
providers have appealed a federal judge's decision upholding a ban 
in Wisconsin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 15:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Zoo Extends Gorilla Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The stork is visiting the Cincinnati Zoo's  
gorilla compound again, extending a national record. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosie, a 25-year-old western lowland gorilla, is expecting. The  
baby, Rosie's eighth, is due in November. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be Cincinnati's 47th gorilla birth, an American record.  
Chicago's Lincoln Park Zoo has had 45. The world record belongs to 
London's Howletts Zoo, which has had 53 births. 
</P>
<P>
	The father is Chaka, a 14-year-old brought to Cincinnati in 1994  
on loan from the Philadelphia Zoo, Curator Mike Dulaney said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990717.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 11:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2000 Looms With Prophecies of Doom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The early forecast for the year 2000 calls for colliding comets,  
sinking continents, mass conflagrations, assorted reigns of terror 
and widespread gnashing of teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	As one millennium fades and another looms, prophets of doom and  
gloom are going into overdrive. Would-be oracles claim harbingers 
of The End are everywhere for the looking -- monstrous floods, 
deadly earthquakes, wars, bombs, the AIDS virus and computer 
viruses. 
</P>
<P>
	Religious fervor is ratcheting up among those who believe 2000  
marks the beginning of the end. Israeli officials are already on 
alert for extremists seeking front-row seats for Christ's second 
coming. The World Wide Web is peppered with sites predicting all 
manner of Earthly ends, ranging from simple planetary destruction 
to space warps. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekly supermarket tabloid Sun summed up the millennial  
mania in a front-page teaser: ``Exact date of Judgment Day -- Are 
you prepared?'' 
</P>
<P>
	No? Take solace, then, in the fact that predictions of  
civilization's demise have been around since civilization's birth. 
Ancient Greek Stoics spoke of the Earth being cleansed by fire. 
Long-ago Hindu writings describe a cycle of cosmic ends and 
rebirths. Europeans in the Middle Ages considered plagues and 
famines early portents of coming disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last century, thousands of believers across New York and  
New England left crops unharvested or gave away cattle after 
farmer-turned-preacher William Miller predicted Christ was coming 
the evening of Oct. 22, 1844. When the fateful night proved less 
than fateful, believers ridiculed Miller's prediction as the 
``Great Disappointment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Christians continue to pin precise dates on Biblical  
prophecies, particularly those from the New Testament's Book of 
Revelation. The book, based on the apostle John's visions of the 
final judgment, is chock-full of horrific detail: men gnawing their 
tongues in agony, rivers of blood, lakes of fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Revelation remains a touchstone for much of Western apocalyptic  
thought, but not the only one. A sampler of doomsday scenarios: 

</P>
<P>
                          	 *NOSTRADAMUS   	
</P>
<P>
	PREDICTION: The 16th century French soothsayer, whose  
predictions still show up in supermarket tabloids, supposedly 
foretold such events as the French Revolution and the rise of 
Hitler -- in quatrains no less. One prediction: 
</P>
<P>
	``In the year 1999 and seven months,  
</P>
<P>
	From the skies will come a Great King of Terror.  
</P>
<P>
	He will bring back to life the King of the Mongols,  
</P>
<P>
	Before and after the war reigns.''  
</P>
<P>
	Who is this terrible king? And is he due this month or in July  
2000? Some interpreters say he is a comet or meteor. Others 
interpret the prediction to mean vast war. 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND OPINION: Many of Nostradamus' vaguely worded predictions  
have been hailed for accuracy -- after the fact. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the Rorschach ink blot test,'' says Paul Kurtz,  
chairman of the Committee for the Scientific Investigation of 
Claims of the Paranormal, located in Amherst, N.Y., outside 
Buffalo. ``You can read into it what you want.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consider this partial verse that supposedly predicted the rise  
of Hitler: 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of the deepest part of the west of Europe;  
</P>
<P>
	From poor people a young child shall be born;  
</P>
<P>
	Who with his tongue shall seduce many people ...''  

</P>
<P>
                          	 *EDGAR CAYCE   	
</P>
<P>
	PREDICTION: The ``sleeping psychic'' from Kentucky put himself  
into hypnotic trances then tuned in telepathically to the minds and 
bodies of faraway people, diagnosed ills and prescribed remedies. 
He also looked into the future: Look for severe weather disruptions 
and worldwide chaos when the Earth's poles ``shift'' in 2000 or 
2001, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND OPINION:   	
</P>
<P>
	Cayce, who died in 1945, also predicted that 1958-98 would be a  
time of earthly tumult, with parts of continents tumbling into the 
seas. Even Cayce's grandson, Charles Thomas Cayce, president of the 
Edgar Cayce Foundation in Virginia, concedes his grandfather's 
forte was distant diagnosis rather than prophesizing doom. 

</P>
<P>
                         	 *LADY OF FATIMA   	
</P>
<P>
	PREDICTION: According to many accounts, the Blessed Mother  
revealed herself to three Portuguese children at Fatima in 1917 and 
told them World War I would end soon but be followed by a second 
war. She then revealed three secrets, including a vision of hell 
and the need for religious devotion. The third secret was sealed 
until 1960, when Pope John XXIII read it and promptly fainted, the 
stories say. He had it resealed. 
</P>
<P>
	A common belief is that the third secret predicted the end of  
the world -- soon -- and that the Vatican keeps it secret for fear it 
would demoralize the masses. 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND OPINION: The Catholic Church never officially sanctioned  
the Fatima story, although some in the church hierarchy give it 
credence, says Father James Wiseman, associate professor of 
theology at Catholic University in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Is there a third secret? Wiseman says if there is, it's likely  
to remain that way. 

</P>
<P>
                         	 *DOOMSDAY CLOCK   	
</P>
<P>
	PREDICTION: The Doomsday Clock, published sporadically in the  
Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, was set in 1947 at seven minutes 
to midnight to represent the impending danger of nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The clock became a prime indicator of the Cold War, the minute  
hand nudging perilously close to midnight when East-West tensions 
heated up. 
</P>
<P>
	Why seven minutes? The clock was designed by a Chicago artist  
married to one of the founding physicists, Alexander Langsdorf. She 
explained the placement of the hands as ``just good design.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND OPINION: The Doomsday Clock was designed with a fail-safe  
feature -- a minute hand that backs up when nuclear tensions ease. 
The scientists rigged their clock so their hypothesis could never 
be proved wrong. The current time is nine minutes to midnight. 

</P>
<P>
                         	 *THE QUICKENING   	
</P>
<P>
	PREDICTION: Definitions of this New Age concept vary, but it's  
easiest to think of it as humanity moving beyond its increasingly 
grim reality to a more spiritual plain. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs that the Quickening is coming, according to adherents,  
include outbreaks of the Ebola virus, a planetary alignment in May 
2000, Hopi Indian prophecies and a purported growth in alien 
abductions. Unfortunately, the Quickening may also be preceded by 
rising oceans and sinking continents. 
</P>
<P>
	SECOND OPINION: Jon Roe, publisher of a New Age magazine called  
the Door Opener, says he's seen numerous apocalyptic predictions 
come and go. One common explanation after prophecies flop is that 
the changes took place just as predicted, but on a ``spiritual'' or 
``energy'' level instead of a physical level, he says. That, of 
course, makes prophecies hard to check out. 

</P>
<P>
	Another complication is that target dates gets squishy as many  
of the prophesized doomsday events draw near. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent hot topic in New Age circles, for instance, was not the  
pending turn of the millennium but the approaching end of a roughly 
5,000-year cycle in the Mayan calendar. That comes in about 13 
years, supposedly to be accompanied by a huge flood or a similar 
catastrophe. 
</P>
<P>
	Says Roe, ``People are beginning to predict that 2012 is more  
important.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
