<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Contributor List Flap Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The controversy over political contributor  
list-swapping at public broadcasting stations is growing, with a 
congressional hearing scheduled for next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may be facing just the tip of the iceberg,'' Ken Johnson,  
spokesman for Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said documents indicate public television stations KQED  
in San Francisco and KCET in Los Angeles and public radio station 
WNYC in New York have provided their donor lists to brokers who, in 
turn, may have provided them to the Democratic Party or other 
political organizations. He would not release the documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, three other television stations, WGBH-TV in Boston,  
WNET in New York and WETA in Washington, D.C., are under scrutiny. 
Also, KERA, a television-radio PBS combination in Dallas, admitted 
Friday it had provided lists to the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin, chairman of the House Commerce telecommunications  
subcommittee, has scheduled a hearing on the matter Tuesday. Rep. 
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., has requested a separate hearing by 
Commerce's oversight subcommittee, which has investigative 
authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin plans to ask for a study by the General Accounting  
Office, Congress' investigative arm, into whether list-swapping 
occurred at other stations or involved individual candidates as 
well as parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a political witch hunt,'' Johnson said. ``If it  
turns out that Republicans have engaged in the same activities, 
we'll take them out to the woodshed too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the midst of the controversy, Republicans have also demanded  
a review of federal funding for public broadcasting. The 
Corporation for Public Broadcasting gets about $250 million a year 
from Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is whether public broadcasting stations violated  
federal tax law by swapping, selling, renting or otherwise 
providing their donor lists to political parties. There is 
typically a three-year statute of limitations on such violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although sharing membership lists is a legitimate business  
practice done daily by countless organizations, the CPB is a 
private, nonprofit entity that's considered a charity for tax 
purposes. As such, it is prohibited from direct or indirect 
intervention in political campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Providing a donor list to a political party or candidate  
wouldn't necessarily constitute an improper intervention, as long 
as all political parties or candidates were given equal access to 
the list. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurel Lambert, KCET's director of advertising and promotions,  
said the station prohibits providing membership lists to political 
organizations. However, the reverse -- the station's buying names 
from both the Democratic and Republican parties -- has occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers, Lambert said, are also told to get station approval for  
any new membership list requests. So far, a search of station 
records hasn't turned up any violations dating back to 1996, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At WNYC, there is also a ban on sharing, selling or renting  
membership lists to political organizations, according to statement 
released by the station late Friday. Tad Roebuck, a spokesman, said 
he didn't know if the station provided lists to brokers. 
</P>
<P>
	At KQED, the station reviewed its records and found that a  
membership list was leased, through a broker, to the Democratic 
National Committee in 1996, said David Shaw, a spokesman. Shaw said 
the station's policy was to exchange lists, one-for-one, with other 
nonprofits, but that is now being revised to excluded exchanges 
with advocacy and political organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	At WGBH, where names have been swapped with the Democratic  
National Committee, officials said they instituted a policy against 
trading names with political organizations in 1994 but continued 
after that because of a ``debt'' incurred by a 1993 list 
acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	After that was resolved, subsequent swapping occurred because of  
administrative error, they said. Officials said they admitted the 
mistake to the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, WNET said it had started an internal investigation  
after learning a list broker working for the station had swapped 
names with the Democratic and Republican parties. 
</P>
<P>
	WETA spokeswoman Cecily Van Praagh said the station traded donor  
lists with the DNC and ``conservative and liberal'' political 
organizations. The station planned to re-evaluate the practice. 
</P>
<P>
	KERA spokeswoman Sharon Philippart said the station discontinued  
the list swapping about two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jenny Backus, spokeswoman for the DNC, said the committee  
obtained the WGBH names through a broker. She said the committee 
always goes through brokers and does not deal directly with 
individual stations. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are standard and routine business practices,'' she said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
