<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Might Reduce Tax Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans may reduce their proposed  
$864 billion tax cut by nearly $72 billion, partly because of 
tricky Senate budget rules and partly to appease rebellious 
moderates in their own ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican aides said Friday that the plan adopted this week by  
the Ways and Means Committee may be scaled back to $792 billion 
over 10 years, the same level as a proposal offered by Sen. William 
Roth, R-Del. 
</P>
<P>
	One key reason, the aides said, is that Senate budget rules  
apparently will only allow a tax cut of the larger size to pass the 
Senate with a simple majority. If the House sent over a large cut, 
it may require approval of 60 of the 100 senators. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to getting as big a bill as possible,'' said  
Trent Duffy, spokesman for the Ways and Means Committee chairman, 
Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas. ``This is being realistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But with a slender majority and Democrats solidly opposed,  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., met with about a dozen GOP 
moderates who have objected that the House tax cut is much too 
large. A GOP aide speaking on condition of anonymity said the lower 
figure may help bring the moderates on board so the bill can clear 
the House next week. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, Republicans and Democrats outlined competing  
plans Friday that are some $500 billion apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth, chairman of the Finance Committee, called his plan an  
effort to ``work in a bipartisan spirit'' by targeting income tax 
cuts at middle-class people, broad expansion of individual 
retirement accounts and 401(k)s and omission of cuts in capital 
gains taxes or repeal of estate taxes as sought by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm optimistic that we will have some Democratic support,''  
Roth said. ``It embodies objectives shared by Republicans, 
Democrats and the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, however, has repeatedly said he will veto any  
tax cut of the size proposed by congressional Republicans. Clinton 
contends it will crowd out money from the $2.9 trillion, 10-year 
surplus he says is needed to ensure the survival of Social Security 
and Medicare and prevent deep cuts in defense and domestic 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything in the $800 billion range fails to meet the  
president's test of doing first things first,'' said Linda Ricci, 
spokeswoman for the White House Office of Management and Budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has proposed cuts of about $250 billion over 10 years,  
including new government-sponsored retirement investment accounts 
that would supplement Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	In an early effort at compromise, Senate Democrats proposed  
splitting the surplus not set aside for Social Security -- an 
estimated $996 billion -- into thirds: one for Medicare, one for net 
tax cuts of $295 billion and one for increased spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be unwise to enact into law permanent, huge tax cuts  
based simply on projections of surpluses,'' said Sen. Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan of New York, senior Democrat on the Finance 
Committee. ``If we enact into law huge tax cuts, a relatively minor 
economic change would push the budget back into deficit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic tax plan would most benefit the middle class by  
raising the standard income tax deduction by 2007 from $7,200 now 
to $11,550 for a married couple and from $4,300 to $5,600 for 
singles. 
</P>
<P>
	It would also benefit two-earner married couples by allowing  
them a new itemized deduction of up to $4,340, if they earn below 
$95,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats, however, say the surplus is so large that bigger  
tax cuts are possible. Sens. John Breaux of Louisiana and Bob 
Kerrey of Nebraska may offer an alternative in the $500 billion 
range when the Finance Committee begins work on the tax cut next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Democratic tax cut is too small and the Republican tax cut  
is too big,'' Breaux said. ``There should be some figure in 
between.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
