<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Company Hurt by Surgeons' Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new type of super glue that closes skin  
lacerations and surgical incisions isn't catching on with doctors 
as quickly as once hoped, leaving the manufacturer with a deep 
wound of its own. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Raleigh, N.C.-based Closure Medical Corp. fell 36  
percent Friday after it disclosed that its distributor, Johnson &AMP; 
Johnson, was cutting back orders for the glue, sold under the name 
Dermabond. Closure on Friday dropped $10.25 to $18 in Nasdaq Stock 
Market trading. 
</P>
<P>
	J&AMP;J spokeswoman Susan Odenthal said doctors need more training  
to know how and when to use the glue instead of traditional 
sutures, and that has slowed demand for the Dermabond. J&AMP;J still 
believes Dermabond will eventually obtain a major portion of the 
wound-care market, partly because it eliminates the need for an 
injection of anesthesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the earliest assumptions at the pace that this would  
become established may have been more ambitious than it turned out 
to be,'' Odenthal said. ``It takes a while for doctors to become 
comfortable with (Dermabond) 
</P>
<P>
	Closure, whose primary product is Dermabond, on Thursday  
reported a second-quarter profit was $15,000, compared to a a loss 
of $2.3 million in the year-ago quarter. Sales rose to $4.28 
million from $1.34 million in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Dermabond has been stocked in about 80 percent of hospital  
emergency room departments, Odenthal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dermabond costs about $25 per application, which is more than  
traditional stitches. It must be administered by doctors and is not 
available for consumer purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has argued the product saves money because it saves  
time for the doctors. Officials from Closure would not return calls 
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Dermabond contains a variation of the chemical used in Super  
Glue. It quickly forms a flexible film over the wound that 
gradually wears off as new skin cells grow beneath it. 
</P>
<P>
	Dermabond is intended to replace stitches in skin-deep cuts. It  
is for topical use only -- not for deep wounds under the skin. For 
larger wounds, doctors still need to use small sutures beneath the 
skin surface. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
