<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Co. Charged in Iran Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A high-tech company that makes equipment  
to diagnose computer problems has been indicted by a federal grand 
jury on charges it violated a 1995 Clinton administration trade 
embargo on selling computer equipment to Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	Microtek International Development Systems, a division of  
Microtek International of Taiwan, manufactures computer-processor 
emulators, which mimic the operation of computer chips at a slower 
speed so operators can troubleshoot problems. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1997, Joe-Pin Ouyang, president of the Hillsboro  
division, began negotiating the sale of emulators to a company in 
Tehran, according to the indictment, which was unsealed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Amir Janversan, an Iranian citizen, and Hamid Janversan of Salt  
Lake City, were charged because they acted as brokers between the 
Iranian buyer and Ouyang and Microtek, the indictment states. 
</P>
<P>
	It claims that in October 1997, more than $100,000 was wired  
from Switzerland and Italy to two credit union accounts in Utah 
controlled by the Janversans, an attempt to hide the identity of 
the purchaser. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Customs agents at Portland International Airport seized the  
emulators Oct. 30, 1997, after an investigation by FBI, Customs and 
Commerce Department agents, said Charles Gorder, an assistant U.S. 
attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment charges Microtek, Ouyang and the Janversans with  
conspiracy, attempting to violate the embargo and money laundering. 
Each defendant could face a maximum of 35 years in prison if 
convicted of all three counts. And Microtek could face fines of as 
much as $1 million, in addition to forfeiting $75,125 it received 
during the alleged illegal transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the company, George Newhouse of Los Angeles, said  
he could not discuss details of the case, but he denied any 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company can say that it has cooperated with the government  
in every respect from the very beginning and is extremely 
disappointed by the decision of the grand jury to proceed with an 
indictment,'' Newhouse said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The export laws are very complicated, and the company and its  
president, Joe-Pin Ouyang, feel they will be completely vindicated 
at trial,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microtek, Ouyang and Hamid Janversan are scheduled to be  
arraigned in federal court in Portland July 30. An arrest warrant 
has been issued for Amir Janversan, who is thought to be in Iran, 
Gorder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Reese, a Portland attorney for Hamid Janversan, said ``he  
believes he will be completely exonerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the Clinton administration imposed the trade embargo  
against Iran after finding it was a threat to U.S. security by 
supporting international terrorists, undermining the Middle East 
peace effort and trying to buy weapons of mass destruction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
