<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Debris From Kennedy Plane Found  
</P>
<P>
	AQUINNAH, Mass. (AP) -- The search is continuing for John F.  
Kennedy Jr., his wife and her sister who disappeared last night 
while flying to Martha's Vineyard. The couple was heading to a 
family wedding in Hyannisport after dropping off Mrs. Kennedy's 
sister on the Vineyard. At Philbin Beach in Aquinnah,''some 
luggage,'' a wheel, a headrest and part of a plane support had 
washed up, said Coast Guard Lt. Craig Jaramillo. However, Rear 
Admiral Richard M. Larrabee said the search would continue. ``I can 
tell you miraculous stories of people surviving,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Bessettes Gather at Conn. Home  
</P>
<P>
	OLD GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- The family of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s  
wife and sister-in-law gathered at their home here today, as 
searchers looked for the small plane the three disappeared in over 
the Atlantic. Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, 33; her older sister, 
Lauren Bessette and Kennedy were en route from Fairfield, N.J. to a 
Kennedy cousin's wedding when they vanished from radar last night. 
Richard Freeman, the sisters' stepfather, declined to comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Overpumping Affects Food Supply  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Overpumping is sucking out too much of the  
world's underground fresh water, with a stable world food supply 
now dependent on an increasing global water deficit, Worldwatch 
Institute said today. Annually, the study estimates, 160 billion 
cubic meters of water is lost to thirsty cities and farms that are 
not returning it to underground aquifers. The biggest known losses 
are in India, China, the United States, North Africa and Saudi 
Arabia. The lost water would be enough to grow 10 percent of world 
grain, said Worldwatch, a nongovernment research group funded by 
grants and sales of its publications. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinians Protest Water Shortage  
</P>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, West Bank (AP) -- Several hundred Palestinians burned  
tires and chanted during a protest today over a water shortage in 
the West Bank. The protesters who blocked the road leading to the 
Deheishe refugee camp with flaming tires said they blamed Israel, 
and not the Palestinian Authority that controls their area, for the 
acute water shortage. Israel controls 80 percent of the aquifers in 
the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. The Palestinians control the 
rest. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Rep. Forbes Joining Democrats  
</P>
<P>
	QUOGUE, N.Y. (AP) -- A Republican switched allegiance to the  
Democrats today, the first such defection since the GOP took 
control of Congress five years ago. Rep. Michael Forbes drew praise 
from President Clinton for having the ``courage to change'' and 
scorn from the GOP for placing ``ego ahead of principle.'' 
Republicans will now hold 222 seats in the 435-member House, with 
211 Democrats and an independent who usually votes with the 
Democrats. One seat is vacant. 

</P>
<P>
	Ohio Zoo Extends Gorilla Record  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The stork is visiting the Cincinnati Zoo's  
gorilla compound again, extending a national record. Rosie, a 
25-year-old western lowland gorilla, is expecting. The baby, 
Rosie's eighth, is due in November. It will be Cincinnati's 47th 
gorilla birth, an American record. Chicago's Lincoln Park Zoo has 
had 45. 

</P>
<P>
	Van de Velde Surges at Carnoustie  
</P>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- A 45-foot birdie putt on the 18th  
gave Jean Van de Velde a round of even-par 70 today and put him in 
a remarkable position -- the only player not over par, a five-stroke 
lead and a chance to become the first qualifier to win the British 
Open since 1962. Only three players broke par in the third round, 
led by the best score of the tournament. Justin Leonard and Craig 
Parry were five behind Van de Velde at 218. 

</P>
<P>
	Pirates Beat Indians 13-10  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Kevin Young and Al Martin each homered twice  
and the Pittsburgh Pirates again turned to big innings to beat the 
Cleveland Indians at their own game, winning 13-10 today. Young 
matched a career high with five RBIs on a two-run homer following 
Martin's two-run shot in the fourth and a three-run drive off 
reliever Steve Reed in the sixth. The second Young homer made it 
11-6 after the Indians had cut Pittsburgh's 7-2 lead to 7-6. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
