<HEADLINE>  Woman Shuttle Captain Nears Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The countdown for the launch of  
NASA's first female space shuttle commander was going well today 
and it seemed as though even the weather would cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia is scheduled to lift off at 12:36 a.m. Tuesday, with  
Air Force Col. Eileen Collins at the controls. The shuttle will 
carry up NASA's $1.5 billion Chandra X-ray Observatory, and the 
five-member crew will set it free seven hours into their flight. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, shuttle weathermen issued a forecast calling for a  
70 percent chance of favorable launch conditions. The only concern 
is a chance of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's countdown clocks began ticking late Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Chandra should have been launched last summer, but was grounded  
by all sorts of problems with the telescope. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
