<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *George E. Brown Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) -- Rep. George E. Brown Jr., the  
oldest member of the House of Representatives who championed 
technological issues ranging from the space race to the Internet, 
died Thursday. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	He was first elected to the House in 1962, representing the 29th  
Congressional District of Los Angeles County for eight years and 
making a name for himself as a foe of the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, he gave up the seat to run for the Senate, but was  
defeated in a primary by Sen. John Tunney. Two years later, he won 
the seat in the 42nd District. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown also championed the establishment of the Environmental  
Protection Agency in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in his career, Brown used his post on the Science  
Committee to support space exploration, both manned and unmanned, 
earning him the title ``Mr. Science.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *Thomas Carlin    	
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- Thomas Carlin, former publisher who guided the  
St. Paul Pioneer Press and Dispatch during a $50 million expansion 
into a new production plant, died Thursday of cancer. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlin was publisher from 1973 until he retired in 1985. He  
joined the newspapers in 1953 as an advertising representative. His 
32-year career with the St. Paul newspapers included stints as 
assistant to the publisher, business manager and general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Carlin is survived by his wife, Verle; children Tom, Mark, Paul,  
Mary Chris, Sara, and Andrew; a brother, Bing; sisters Lucia Seidel 
and Patricia; and 11 grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jeff Jordan    	
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Jeff Jordan, a widely known Omaha television  
anchor and newspaper columnist, died Thursday of a brain tumor. He 
was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan came to Omaha in 1970 as the evening news anchor at Omaha  
television station KMTV, now a CBS affiliate. He was there eight 
years before going to work in 1979 at the Omaha World-Herald, where 
he worked until 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan later started his own communications consulting firm. In  
1985, he went to work for Union Pacific Railroad, where two of his 
video scripts won national awards. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Jordan was promoted to manager of communications  
consulting at UP and was named director of corporate communications 
for UP's Overnite Transportation in Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Before arriving in Omaha, Jordan worked at WGN radio and TV in  
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan retired last year.  

</P>
<P>
                        *Andre Franco Montoro    	
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Congressman Andre Franco Montoro, a  
former governor of Sao Paulo state and one of the chief architects 
of Brazil's return to civilian rule, died Friday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1970s Montoro helped found the Brazilian Democratic  
Movement, the only legal opposition to the military regime that 
ruled Brazil between 1964 and 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	As governor of Brazil's largest, wealthiest and most populous  
state from 1983 to 1987, he helped organize and lead the nationwide 
``Direct Elections-Now'' campaign that opened the way for civilian 
rule. 
</P>
<P>
	After losing his bid for a senate seat in the 1990 election, he  
was elected to the Chamber of Deputies in 1994. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Charles P. Roman    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles P. Roman, the New York City advertising  
pioneer who turned bodybuilder Charles Atlas into an icon of 
American manhood, died Friday. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman came up with the Atlas ``Dynamic-Tension'' trademark, as  
well as the ``I was a 97 pound weakling'' slogan. He also devised 
the long-running comic strip ad in which a brawny bully kicks sand 
in the face of a skinny man, who then takes the Atlas course, 
becomes muscle-bound and knocks out the bully. The slogan and the 
incident at the beach were based on the life of Atlas, who was 
sickly as a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Roman met Atlas in 1928. By then, Atlas was already a champion  
bodybuilder. They soon formed a partnership, Charles Atlas Ltd., of 
which Roman became sole owner in 1969, 3 years before Atlas' death. 
Roman sold the company in 1997. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
