<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Dress Codes at Some Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Now it's teachers who might be sent to  
the principal's office if their clothes aren't up to par. 
</P>
<P>
	A school board southeast of Nashville is joining several  
districts nationwide in setting standards for the way its teachers 
dress: no sleeveless dresses, revealing skirts, low-cut shirts or 
sweat pants. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted our teachers to look professional. For the most part  
they do ... but there were a few coaches who would wear sweat pants 
all day long,'' Cannon County school board member Glenda Harris 
said Friday of the district's new dress codes. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades, students have been scrutinized by school officials  
who could send them home for inappropriate clothing. In fact, the 
Cannon County school board included a dress code and optional 
uniform for students in its directive last week. 
</P>
<P>
	But it also included strict guidelines for teachers, teacher  
assistants and secretaries in the system's seven schools. 
</P>
<P>
	In Denver, banned teacher attire includes mid-thigh skirts,  
Spandex, tube tops and thongs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important kids learn that appearance does matter,''  
Denver school board member Laura Lefkowits said after the district 
adopted the guidelines in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Gentry, a middle school principal in Warner Robins, Ga.,  
about 90 miles southeast of Atlanta, wants to take the dress code 
idea a step further -- he would like to see school uniforms for 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that school uniforms worn by the entire faculty  
would present a positive, professional image to both our parents 
and students,'' he wrote in a recent letter to faculty members. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers would wear khaki or navy pants, skirts or jumpers  
starting in the 2000-2001 school year, with student uniforms 
required the following year. The school board hasn't yet considered 
his request. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tennessee, the Cannon County school dress guidelines came  
from a committee that included a teacher and principal from each 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee Education Association spokesman Jerry Winters, whose  
association represents teachers, said he had never heard of teacher 
dress codes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's a crying need for it,'' he said,  
explaining that a principal can talk individually with a faculty 
member who is dressed inappropriately. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``It's reasonable to expect any professional to  
project a professional image. In order to get respect, you need to 
look respectable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Bush, a teacher and coach at Cannon County High School,  
said he sometimes wore a warm-up suit in a history class wedged 
between two wellness classes. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the new guidelines may make it difficult for him to  
change clothes and make it to class on time. Still, he welcomes the 
dress code, saying it will set an example for students and require 
his female colleagues to dress more modestly . 
</P>
<P>
	``I always felt a little uncomfortable wearing that warm-up suit  
in history class,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
