<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-22 Fighter Suffers New Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pentagon efforts to save the F-22 fighter  
suffered another blow when the House Appropriations Committee 
endorsed a recommendation to suspend production. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel went along Friday with the decision of its defense  
subcommittee to spend $1.8 billion on buying more current fighter 
jets and to increase bonuses for military pilots instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel then approved an overall $266.1 billion defense  
spending bill, sending it to the full House for a vote later this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall bill, for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, is  
$15.5 billion above spending in the current fiscal year and $2.8 
billion more than requested by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	It includes money for a 4.8 percent across-the-board military  
pay raise beginning in January, up from the 4.4 percent increase 
Clinton requested. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also includes $94 million to upgrade ``readiness  
shortfalls'' in the Army's Apache attack helicopter program. 
</P>
<P>
	The money was included after the commander of the 24 Apache  
helicopters sent to the Balkans, Brig. Gen. Richard Cody, 
complained last month of equipment and pilot training inadequacies. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopters were sent to Albania. None flew against Serb  
forces. But two crewmen were killed when two helicopters crashed in 
a night training exercise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon had requested $3 billion for the F-22 program. The  
Air Force considers the costly and sophisticated fighter to be its 
top warplane in the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the $3 billion, $1.8 billion was to go to buying six of the  
new planes from Lockheed Martin Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon mounted a heavy lobbying campaign this week to try  
to save the program. A Senate-passed bill contains the full $3 
billion for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
