<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-17 01:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Warns of Defect in Clot-Buster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shortages of the clot-busting drug Abbokinase  
will continue for the foreseeable future. The government has issued 
a stern letter saying maker Abbott Laboratories still has not 
corrected important safety defects. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals have experienced shortages of Abbokinase, one of many  
drugs used to dissolve blood clots, since last fall. That's when 
the Food and Drug Administration suspended Abbokinase sales, saying 
Abbott failed to ensure the drug's ingredients -- the kidney cells 
of foreign newborns who died -- were free of hepatitis B and other 
infections. 
</P>
<P>
	Subsequently, viral and bacterial contamination has been found  
in the factory, as well as additional problems with testing the 
donor kidney cells, the FDA said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	No contamination was found in any Abbokinase sold for patient  
use -- the drug is pasteurized before sale. So the FDA has never 
ordered a recall of the scarce supplies that some hospitals still 
have on pharmacy shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FDA has urged doctors to use remaining Abbokinase  
supplies only in emergencies, saying it does have the potential to 
contain infections. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the FDA asked doctors Friday to report any infections  
that might be attributable to Abbokinase, used to dissolve blood 
clots in lungs and heart arteries and to clear hospital patients' 
catheters. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday, almost a year after the FDA first uncovered problems,  
the government wrote Abbott that it still had not corrected serious 
defects. One concern, the agency said, is that the manufacturing 
defects could lead to Abbokinase contamination not yet discovered. 
</P>
<P>
	An Abbott spokeswoman would not say why it is taking so long to  
correct the problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Abbott is continuing to work with the FDA and we're committed  
to resolving the remaining issues,'' said spokeswoman Rhonda 
Luniak. 
</P>
<P>
	A consumer advocate urged FDA to recall remaining Abbokinase.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how much more evidence of serious,  
health-threatening problems there have to be before FDA lowers the 
boom,'' said Dr. Sidney Wolfe of the advocacy group Public Citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbott cannot begin selling Abbokinase again until it institutes  
proper testing of the kidney cells and proper processes to safely 
store and handle ingredients and sterilize the product, the FDA 
said Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
